# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: pomace
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] The history of viticulture in Tuscany dates back to its settlements by the Etruscans in the 8th century BC.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] Amphora remnants originating in the region show that Tuscan wine was exported to southern Italy and Gaul as early as the 7th century BC.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] By the 3rd century BC, there were literary references by Greek writers about the quality of Tuscan wine.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] From the fall of the Roman Empire and throughout the Middle Ages, monasteries were the main purveyors of wines in the region.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] As the aristocratic and merchant classes emerged, they inherited the sharecropping system of agriculture known as *mezzadria*.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] This system took its name from the arrangement whereby the landowner provides the land and resources for planting in exchange for half (*mezza*) of the yearly crop.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] Many Tuscan landowners would turn their half of the grape harvest into wine that would be sold to merchants in Florence.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] The earliest reference of Florentine wine retailers dates to 1079 and a guild was created in 1282.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] The *Arte dei Vinattieri* guild established strict regulations on how the Florentine wine merchants could conduct business.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] No wine was to be sold within 100 yards (91 m) of a church.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] Wine merchants were also prohibited from serving children under age 15 or to prostitutes, ruffians and thieves.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] In the 14th century, an average of 7.9 million US gallons (30,000 m3) of wine was sold every year in Florence.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] The earliest references to Vino Nobile di Montepulciano wine date to the late 14th century.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] The first recorded mention of wine from Chianti was by the Tuscan merchant Francesco di Marco Datini, the "merchant of Prato", who described it as a light, white wine.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] The Vernaccia and Greco wines of San Gimignano were considered luxury items and treasured as gifts over saffron.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] During this period Tuscan winemakers began experimenting with new techniques and invented the process of *governo* which helped to stabilize the wines and ferment the sugar content sufficiently to make them dry.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] In 1685 the Tuscan author Francesco Redi wrote *Bacco in Toscana*, a 980-line poem describing the wines of Tuscany.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] Following the end of the Napoleonic Wars, Tuscany returned to the rule of the Habsburgs.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] It was at this point that the statesman Bettino Ricasoli inherited his family ancestral estate in Broglio located in the heart of the Chianti Classico zone.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] Determined to improve the estate, Ricasoli traveled throughout Germany and France, studying the grape varieties and viticultural practices.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] He imported several of the varieties back to Tuscany and experimented with different varieties in his vineyards.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] However, in his experiments Ricasoli discovered that three local varieties—Sangiovese, Canaiolo and Malvasia—produced the best wine.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] In 1848, revolutions broke out in Italy and Ricasoli's beloved wife died, leaving him with little interest to devote to wine.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] In the 1850s Oidium *Erysiphe necator* and war devastated most of Tuscany's vineyards with many peasant farmers leaving for other parts of Italy or to emigrate to the Americas.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] Under the *mezzadria* employment arrangement, most of the wine produced by peasants was drunk by their landlords.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] Peasants stretched their meagre supply with water, labelling the resulting drink *l'acqua pazza* (lit.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] Tuscany (which includes seven coastal islands) is Italy's fifth largest region.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] It is bordered to the northwest by Liguria, the north by Emilia-Romagna, Umbria to the east and Lazio to the south.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] To the west is the Tyrrhenian Sea which gives the area a warm Mediterranean climate.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] The terrain is quite hilly (over 68% of the terrain), progressing inward to the Apennine Mountains along the border with Emilia-Romagna.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] The hills have a tempering effect on the summertime heat, with many vineyards planted on the higher elevations of the hillsides.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] The Sangiovese grape performs better when it can receive more direct sunlight, which is a benefit of the many hillside vineyards in Tuscany.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] The majority of the region's vineyards are found at altitudes of 500–1,600 ft (150–490 m).
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] The higher elevations also increase the diurnal temperature variation, helping the grapes maintain their balance of sugars and acidity as well as their aromatic qualities.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] After Piedmont and the Veneto, Tuscany produces the third highest volume of DOC/G quality wines.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] Tuscany is Italy's third most planted region (behind Sicily and Apulia) but it is eighth in production volume.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] This is partly because the soil of Tuscany is very poor, and producers emphasize low yields and higher quality levels in their wine.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] More than 80% of the region's production is red wine.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] The Sangiovese grape is Tuscany's most prominent grape; however, many different clonal varieties exist, as many towns have their own local version of Sangiovese.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] Cabernet Sauvignon has been planted in Tuscany for over 250 years, but has only recently become associated with the region due to the rise of the Super Tuscans.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] Other international varieties found in Tuscany include Cabernet franc, Chardonnay, Merlot, Pinot noir, Sauvignon blanc and Syrah.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] Of the many local red grape varieties Canaiolo, Colorino, Malvasia nera and Mammolo are the most widely planted.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] For Tuscan white wines, Trebbiano is the most widely planted variety followed by Malvasia, Vermentino and Vernaccia.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] Super Tuscans are an unofficial category of Tuscan wines, not recognized within the Italian wine classification system.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] Although an extraordinary number of wines claim to be "the first Super Tuscan," most would agree that this credit belongs to Sassicaia, the brainchild of marchese Mario Incisa della Rocchetta, who planted Cabernet Sauvignon at his Tenuta San Guido estate in Bolgheri back in 1944.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] It was for many years the marchese's personal wine, until, starting with the 1968 vintage, it was released commercially in 1971.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] The growth of Super Tuscans is also rooted in the restrictive DOC practices of the Chianti zone prior to the 1990s.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] During this time Chianti could be composed of no more than 70% Sangiovese and had to include at least 10% of one of the local white wine grapes.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] Producers who deviated from these regulations could not use the Chianti name on their wine labels and would be classified as *vino da tavola*—Italy's lowest wine designation.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] By the 1970s, the consumer market for Chianti wines was suffering and the wines were widely perceived to be lacking quality.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] Many Tuscan wine producers thought they could produce a better quality wine if they were not hindered by the DOC regulations.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] The marchese Piero Antinori was one of the first to create a "Chianti-style" wine that ignored the DOC regulations, releasing a 1971 Sangiovese–Cabernet Sauvignon blend known as *Tignanello* in 1978.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] He was inspired by Sassicaia, of which he was given the sale agency by his uncle Mario Incisa della Rocchetta.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] Other producers followed suit and soon the prices for these Super Tuscans were consistently beating the prices of some of most well known Chianti.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] Rather than rely on name recognition of the Chianti region, the Super Tuscan producers sought to create a wine brand that would be recognizable on its own merits by consumers.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] By the late 1980s, the trend of creating high-quality non-DOC wines had spread to other regions of Tuscany, as well as Piedmont and Veneto.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] Modification to the Chianti DOC regulation attempted to "correct" the issues of Super Tuscans, so that many of the original Super Tuscans would now qualify as standard DOC/G Chianti.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] Most producers have brought their Super Tuscans back under legal regulations, notably since the creation of the less restrictive IGT *Toscana* designation in 1992 and the DOC Bolgheri designation in 1994, while the pioneer Sassicaia was prized with its own exclusive Bolgheri Sassicaia DOC.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] In addition to wines based on the Sangiovese grape, many well known Super Tuscans are based on a "Bordeaux-blend", meaning a combination of grapes typical for Bordeaux (especially Cabernet Sauvignon and Merlot).
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] These grapes are not originally from the region, but imported and planted later.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] The climate in Tuscany has proven to be very good for these grapes.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] While Tuscany is not the only Italian region to make the *passito* dessert wine Vin Santo (meaning "holy wine"), the Tuscan versions of the wine are well regarded and sought for by wine consumers.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] The best-known version is from the Chianti Classico and is produced with a blend of Trebbiano and Malvasia Bianca.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] Red and rosé styles are also produced mostly based on the Sangiovese grape.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] The wines are aged in barrels for a minimum of three years, four if it is meant to be a *Riserva*.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] Tuscany's 41 DOC and 11 DOCG are spread out across the region's ten provinces.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] Brunello is the name of the local Sangiovese variety that is grown around the village of Montalcino.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] Located south of the Chianti Classico zone, the Montalcino range is drier and warmer than Chianti.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] Monte Amiata shields the area from the winds coming from the southeast.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] Many of the area's vineyards are located on the hillsides leading up towards the mountain to elevations of around 1,640 ft (500 m) though some vineyards can be found in lower-lying areas.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] The wines of northern and eastern regions tend to ripen more slowly and produce more perfumed and lighter wines.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] The southern and western regions are warmer, and the resulting wines tend to be richer and more intense.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] The Brunello variety of Sangiovese seems to flourish in this *terroir*, ripening easily and consistently producing wines of deep color, extract, richness with full bodies and good balance of tannins.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] In the mid-19th century, a local farmer named Clemente Santi is believed to have isolated the Brunello clone and planted it in this region.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] His grandson Ferruccio Biondi-Santi helped to popularize Brunello di Montalcino in the later half of the 19th century.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] In the 1980s, it was the first wine to earn the DOCG classification.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] Today there are about two hundred growers in the Montalcino region producing about 333,000 cases of Brunello di Montalcino a year.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] Brunello di Montalcino wines are required to be aged for at least four years prior to being released, with *riserva* wines needing five years.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] Brunellos tend to be very tight and tannic in their youth, needing at least a decade or two before they start to soften with wines from excellent vintages having the potential to do well past 50 years.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] In 1984, the Montalcino region was granted the DOC designation *Rosso di Montalcino*.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] Often called Baby Brunellos, these wines are typically made from the same grapes, vineyards and style as the regular Brunello di Montalcino but are not aged as long.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] While similar to Brunellos in flavor and aromas, these wines are often lighter in body and more approachable in their youth.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] The Carmignano region was one of the first Tuscan regions to be permitted to use Cabernet Sauvignon and Cabernet Franc in their DOC wines since those varieties had a long history of being grown in the region.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] Noted for the quality of its wines since the Middle Ages, Carmignano was identified by Cosimo III de' Medici, Grand Duke of Tuscany as one of the superior wine producing areas of Tuscany and granted special legal protections in 1716.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] In the 18th century, the producers of the Carmignano region developed a tradition of blending Sangiovese with Cabernet Sauvignon, long before the practice became popularized by the "Super Tuscan" of the late 20th century.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] In 1975, the region was awarded *denominazione di origine controllata* (DOC) status and subsequently promoted to *denominazione di origine controllata e garantita* (DOCG) status in 1990 (retroactive to the 1988 vintage).
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] Today Carmignano has approximately 270 acres (110 ha) planted, producing nearly 71,500 US gallons (271,000 L) of DOCG designated wine a year.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] Located in the central region of Tuscany, the Chianti zone is Tuscany's largest classified wine region and produces over eight million cases a year.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] In addition to producing the well known red Chianti wine, the Chianti zone also produces white, other *Rosso* reds and Vin Santo.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] The region is split into two DOCG- Chianti and Chianti Classico.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] The Chianti Classico zone covers the area between Florence and Siena, which is the original Chianti region, and where some of the best expressions of Chianti wine are produced.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] Since 1996, Chianti is permitted to include as little as 75% Sangiovese, a maximum of 10% Canaiolo, up to 10% of the white wine grapes Malvasia and Trebbiano and up to 15% of any other red wine grape grown in the region, such as Cabernet Sauvignon.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] This variety of grapes and usage is one reason why Chianti can vary widely from producer to producer.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] The use of white grapes in the blend could alter the style of Chianti by softening the wines with a higher percentage of white grapes, typically indicating that the wine is meant to be drunk younger and not aged for long.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] In general, Chianti Classicos are described as medium-bodied wines with firm, dry tannins.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] The characteristic aroma is cherry but it can also carry nutty and floral notes as well.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] In 2006, the use of white grapes Trebbiano and Malvasia was prohibited (except in Chianti Colli Senesi until the 2015 vintage).
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] Local laws also require wines to have a minimum of 70% Sangiovese (and 80% for the more prestigious Chianti Classico DOCG).
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] The native varieties Canaiolo and Colorino are also permitted, as are the international classics, Cabernet Sauvignon and Merlot, to a limited degree.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] The Chianti Classico region covers approximately 100 mi2 (260 km2) and includes the communes of Castellina, Gaiole, Greve and Radda and Panzano, as well as parts of four other neighboring communes.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] The *terroir* of the Classico zone varies throughout the region depending on the vineyards' altitude, soil type and distance from the Arno River.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] The soils of the northern communes, such as Greve, are richer in clay deposits while those in the southern communes, like Gaiole, are harder and stonier.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] *Riserva* Chianti is aged for at least 27 months, some of it in oak, and must have a minimum alcohol content of 12.5%.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] Wines from the Chianti DOCG can carry the name of one of the six sub-zones or just the Chianti designation.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] The Chianti Superiore designation refers to wines produced in the provinces of Florence and Siena but not in the Classico zone.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] The DOC Bolgheri region of the Livorno province is home to one of the original Super Tuscan wines Sassicaia, first made in 1944 produced by the marchesi Incisa della Rochetta, cousin of the Antinori family.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] The DOC Bolgheri region is also home to the Super Tuscan wine Ornellaia which was featured in the film *Mondovino* as well as Tignanello from Marchesi Antinori.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] Vernaccia di San Gimignano is a white wine made from the Vernaccia grape in the areas around San Gimignano.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] In 1966, it was the first wine to receive a DOC designation.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] This wine style has been made in the area for over seven centuries.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] The wine is dry and full-bodied with earthy notes of honey and minerals.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] In some styles it can be made to emphasize the fruit more and some producers have experimented with aging or fermenting the wine in oak barrels in order to give the wine a sense of creaminess or toastiness.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] The Vino Nobile di Montepulciano received its DOCG status shortly after Brunello di Montalcino, in 1980.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] The DOCG covers the red wine of the Montepulciano area.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] The wine received its name in the 17th century, when it was the favorite wine of the Tuscan nobility.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] Located in the southeastern region of Tuscany, the climate of the region is strongly influenced by the sea.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] The variety of Sangiovese in Montepulciano is known as Prugnolo Gentile and is required to account for at least 80% of the wine.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] Traditionally Canaiolo and Mammolo make up the remaining part of the blend but some producers have begun to experiment with Cabernet Sauvignon and Merlot.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] The wines are required to age two years prior to release, with an additional year if it is to be a *riserva*.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] The recent use of French oak barrels has increased the body and intensity of the wines which are noted for their plummy fruit, almond notes and smooth tannins.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] In Etruscan times, Valdichiana, an area which presently stretches along the Southeastern part of Tuscany up to the Florence-Rome road ramification, was called the "Breadbasket of Etruria".
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] However, its hills were already dotted with vineyards.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] Later on, Plinius the Elder would describe the quality of these wines as follows: Talpone (red) and Ethesiaca (white).
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] This was a vine growing culture spreading over the hills of the Tuscan part of Valdichiana surrounding the important commercial centres of Foiano della Chiana, Lucignano, Cortona, Montepulciano and Arezzo.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] The importance given to this economical activity was confirmed in the following years in successive stages in the writings of the Bishopric of Arezzo in *Valdichiana Champagne*.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] During the 1800s, the merchants of Bourgogne and Champagne decided to use the wines of Tuscan Valdichiana due to their renowned quality as a base for their champagnes after the phylloxera or vine-pest had destroyed their vineyards.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] The wine making tradition was enriched and endorsed in the late 1960s and early 1970s with the DOC guarantee of origin recognition thanks to the effort of few noble families such as Della Stufa (Castello del Calcione, Lucignano) and Mancini Griffoli (Fattoria Santa Vittoria, Pozzo della Chiana).
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] The first policy document of 1972 only protected the denomination of the "Virgin White Valdichiana" type.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] Later, the policy document was modified and enriched to include the entire selection of wines produced in the Tuscan Valdichiana.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] In 1989, the DOC guarantee of origin was extended to the sparkling and spumante types.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] In 1993, output was lowered and modified.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] Later, in 1999, a production policy was put in action for white berry types (chardonnay and grechetto), red berry types (red, rosato, sangiovese), and Vin Santo, thus fulfilling the aspirations of the producers after more than thirty years.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] This allowed the plan of promotion to strengthen the fundamental, unique, strong, and essential bond with its territory.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] The Pomino region near Rufina has been historically known for the prevalence of the French wine grape varieties, making wines from both Cabernets as well as Chardonnay, Merlot, Pinot blanc, Pinot grigio in addition to the local Italian varieties.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] The Frescobaldi family is one of the area's most prominent wine producers.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] In southern Tuscany, towards the region of Latium, is the area of Maremma which has its own IGT designation *Maremma Toscana*.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] Maremma is also home to Tuscany's newest DOCG, Morellino di Scansano, which makes a fragrant, dry Sangiovese based wine.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] The province of Grosseto is one of Tuscany's emerging wine regions with eight DOC designations, half of which were created in the late 1990s.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] It includes the Monteregio di Massa Marittima region which has been recently the recipient of foreign investment in the area's wine, especially by "flying winemakers".
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] The Parrina region is known for its white wine blend of Trebbiano and Ansonica.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] The wine Bianco di Pitigliano is known for its eclectic mix of white wine grapes in the blend including Chardonnay, the Greco sub variety of Trebbiano, Grechetto, Malvasia, Pinot blanc, Verdello and Welschriesling.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] In Maremma, a hidden gem with many wineries, is Poggio Argentiera winery which makes Morellino di Scansano and other wines.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] The wines of Montecarlo region include several varieties that are not commonly found in Tuscan wines including Sémillon and Roussanne.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] The minor Chianti grape Ciliegiolo is also popular here.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] The island of Elba has one of the longest winemaking histories in Tuscany and is home to its own DOC.
[src:pomace/acqua-pazza-wine] Some of the wines produced here include a sparkling Trebbiano wine, a sweet Ansonica *passito*, and a semi-sweet dessert wine from Aleatico.
[src:pomace/alcohol-concern] In 2007 it became one of the 24 founding member organisations of Alcohol Health Alliance UK, a coalition of medical, charity and campaign organisations related to alcohol.
[src:pomace/alcohol-concern] In April 2017, Alcohol Concern merged with Alcohol Research UK, and in November 2018 the merged group was named Alcohol Change UK.
[src:pomace/alcohol-concern] It is now recognised as a national agency on alcohol misuse for the UK.
[src:pomace/alcohol-concern] Since September 2017, the charity has been led by Chief Executive Officer Dr Richard Piper, previously of Roald Dahl's Marvellous Medicine Children's Charity.
[src:pomace/alcohol-concern] In May 2012, Alcohol Concern began promoting the Dry January challenge, a national campaign in the UK for people to give up drinking alcohol for the month of January each year.
[src:pomace/alcohol-concern] The first Dry January challenge was in 2013.
[src:pomace/alcohol-concern] The idea came from Emily Robinson, who gave up alcohol for January 2011 in preparation for a half marathon and joined Alcohol Concern in January 2012 while abstaining again.
[src:pomace/alcohol-concern] Public Health England began promoting the campaign in December 2014.
[src:pomace/alcohol-concern] In its first year, 4,000 people signed up for the Dry January challenge and it has grown in popularity ever since with nearly 9 million people planning to take a month off drinking in 2023.
[src:pomace/alcohol-concern] Other countries are interested in bringing the Dry January challenge to their own populations with the Dry January campaign being licensed to take place in France, Switzerland, Norway, Austria, South Tyrol (Italy), and the USA.
[src:pomace/alcohol-concern] Alcohol Awareness Week is run and managed by Alcohol Change UK.
[src:pomace/alcohol-concern] Each year, Alcohol Change UK sets the date and theme for the upcoming campaign and shares free digital resources for people to take part.
[src:pomace/alcohol-concern] The campaign has moved from its previous spot in November and now takes place every July.
[src:pomace/alcohol-concern] Alcohol Change UK offers training and consultancy services for professionals working in healthcare, housing and homelessness, social care, academia, or the emergency services, as well as in the workplace, to improve their policies and practices in supporting people with their drinking.
[src:pomace/alcohol-concern] Its flagship Blue Light approach helps to better support people with the most serious and chronic alcohol problems, who often have multiple needs.
[src:pomace/alcohol-concern] Alcohol Change UK funds, commissions, and conducts research to strengthen the evidence base and improve the lives of those affected by alcohol harm.
[src:pomace/alcohol-concern] Alcohol Change UK acts as the secretariat and public enquiry point for the All-Party Parliamentary Group (APPG) on Alcohol Harm, which exists to discuss alcohol-related issues and make related recommendations to government.
[src:pomace/alcohol-concern] The current chair of the group is Christian Wakeford MP.
[src:pomace/alcohol-concern] Alcohol Change UK is an independent charity, with income from an investment fund, grants, donations from supporters, and charges for consultancy and training.
[src:pomace/alcohol-content] France, alcohol by volume is often referred to as **degrees Gay-Lussac** (after the French chemist Joseph Louis Gay-Lussac), although there is a slight difference since the Gay-Lussac convention uses the International Standard Atmosphere value for temperature, 15 °C (59 °F).
[src:pomace/alcohol-content] Mixing two solutions of alcohol of different strengths usually causes a change in volume.
[src:pomace/alcohol-content] Mixing pure water with a solution less than 24% by mass causes a slight increase in total volume, whereas the mixing of two solutions above 24% causes a decrease in volume.
[src:pomace/alcohol-content] The phenomenon of volume changes due to mixing dissimilar solutions is called "partial molar volume".
[src:pomace/alcohol-content] Water and ethanol are both polar solvents.
[src:pomace/alcohol-content] When water is added to ethanol, the smaller water molecules are attracted to the ethanol's hydroxyl group, and each molecule alters the polarity field of the other.
[src:pomace/alcohol-content] The attraction allows closer spacing between molecules than is usually found in non-polar mixtures.
[src:pomace/alcohol-content] Thus, alc/vol is not the same as volume fraction expressed as a percentage.
[src:pomace/alcohol-content] Volume fraction, which is widely used in chemistry (commonly denoted as v/v), is defined as the volume of a particular component divided by the sum of all components in the mixture when they are measured separately.
[src:pomace/alcohol-content] For example, to make 100 mL of 50% alc/vol ethanol solution, water would be added to 50 mL of ethanol to make up exactly 100 mL.
[src:pomace/alcohol-content] Whereas to make a 50% v/v ethanol solution, 50 mL of ethanol and 50 mL of water could be mixed but the resulting volume of solution will measure less than 100 mL due to the change of volume on mixing, and will contain a higher concentration of ethanol.
[src:pomace/alcohol-content] The difference is not large, with the maximum difference being less than 2.5%, and less than 0.5% difference for concentrations under 20%.
[src:pomace/alcohol-content] Some drinks have requirements of alcoholic content in order to be certified as a certain alcohol brand or label.
[src:pomace/alcohol-content] For example, in the United Kingdom, the United States, Canada and European Union whisky is legally required to be no less than 40% ABV bottled.
[src:pomace/alcohol-content] Low-alcohol beers (<0.5) are considered in some countries such as Iran as permitted (halal) despite alcohol being banned.
[src:pomace/alcohol-content] However, the level of alcohol-free beers is typically the lowest commercially sold 0.05.
[src:pomace/alcohol-content] It is near impossible for a healthy person to become intoxicated drinking low-alcohol drinks.
[src:pomace/alcohol-content] The low concentration severely limits the rate of intake, which is easily dispatched by human metabolism.
[src:pomace/alcohol-content] Quickly drinking 1.5 L of 0.4% alc/vol beer in an hour resulted in a maximum of 0.0056% BAC in a study of German volunteers.
[src:pomace/alcohol-content] Healthy human kidneys can only excrete 0.8–1.0 L of water per hour, making water intoxication likely to set in before any alcoholic intoxication.
[src:pomace/alcohol-content] The process of ethanol fermentation will slow down and eventually come to a halt as the alcohol produced becomes too concentrated for the yeast to tolerate, defining an upper limit of alc/vol for non-distilled alcoholic drinks.
[src:pomace/alcohol-content] The typical tolerance for beer yeasts is at 8–12%, while wine yeasts typically range from 14–18%, with speciality ones reaching 20% alc/vol.
[src:pomace/alcohol-content] Any higher would require distillation, producing liquor.
[src:pomace/alcohol-content] Details about typical amounts of alcohol contained in various beverages can be found in the articles about them.
[src:pomace/alcohol-content] During the production of wine and beer, yeast is added to a sugary solution.
[src:pomace/alcohol-content] During fermentation, the yeasts consume the sugars and produce alcohol.
[src:pomace/alcohol-content] The density of sugar in water is greater than the density of alcohol in water.
[src:pomace/alcohol-content] A hydrometer is used to measure the change in specific gravity (SG) of the solution before and after fermentation.
[src:pomace/alcohol-content] The volume of alcohol in the solution can then be estimated.
[src:pomace/alcohol-content] There are a number of empirical formulae which brewers and winemakers use to estimate the alcohol content of the liquor made.
[src:pomace/alcohol-content] Specific gravity is the density of a liquid relative to that of water, i.e., if the density of the liquid is 1.05 times that of water, it has a specific gravity of 1.05.
[src:pomace/alcohol-content] In UK brewing usage, it is customary to regard the reference value for water to be 1000, so the specific gravity of the same example beer would be quoted as 1050.
[src:pomace/alcohol-content] The formulas here assume that the former definition is used for specific gravity.
[src:pomace/alcohol-content] During ethanol fermentation the yeast converts one mole of sugar into two moles of alcohol.
[src:pomace/alcohol-content] where 46.069 is the molar mass of ethanol and 180.156 is the molar mass of glucose and fructose.
[src:pomace/alcohol-content] SG can be measured using an hydrometer and Brix can be calculated from SG.
[src:pomace/alcohol-content] SG drop is how much the SG decreased during fermentation (at 20 degree C).
[src:pomace/alcohol-content] The factor 135 is most accurate in the center of the SG drop range of 0.000 to 0.179.
[src:pomace/alcohol-content] Advanced formula derived from Carl Balling empirical formulas.
[src:pomace/alcohol-content] The formula compensates for changes in SG with changes in alcohol concentration and for the fact that not all sugar is converted into alcohol.
[src:pomace/alcohol-content] where SG final is the specific gravity when fermentation ends, Plato start is the sugar by weight when fermentation begins, Plato final is the sugar by weight when fermentation ends.
[src:pomace/alcohol-content] Brix can be used instead of Plato as they are nearly identical.
[src:pomace/alcohol-content] Another way of specifying the amount of alcohol content is alcohol *proof*, which in the United States is twice the alcohol-by-volume (alc/vol) number.
[src:pomace/alcohol-content] This may lead to confusion over similar products bought in varying regions that have different names on country-specific labels.
[src:pomace/alcohol-content] For example, Stroh rum that is 80% ABV is advertised and labeled as *Stroh 80* when sold in Europe, but is named *Stroh 160* when sold in the United States.
[src:pomace/alcohol-content] In the United Kingdom, proof is 1.75 times the number (expressed as a percentage).
[src:pomace/alcohol-content] For example, 40% alc/vol is 80 proof in the US and 70 proof in the UK.
[src:pomace/alcohol-content] However, since 1980, alcohol proof in the UK has been replaced by alc/vol as a measure of alcohol content, avoiding confusion between the UK and US proof standards.
[src:pomace/alcohol-content] In the United States, Arkansas, Kansas, Mississippi, South Carolina, and Tennessee regulate and tax alcoholic beverages according to **alcohol by weight** (**ABW**), expressed as a percentage of total mass.
[src:pomace/alcohol-content] The alc/vol value of a beverage is always higher than the ABW.
[src:pomace/alcohol-content] Because ABW measures the proportion of the drink's mass which is alcohol, while alc/vol is the proportion of the drink's volume which is alcohol, the two values are in the same proportion as the drink's density is with the density of alcohol.
[src:pomace/alcohol-content] At relatively low alc/vol, the alcohol percentage by weight is about 4/5 of the alc/vol (e.g., 3.2% ABW is about 4% alc/vol).
[src:pomace/alcohol-content] However, because of the miscibility of alcohol and water, the conversion factor is not constant but rather depends upon the concentration of alcohol.
[src:pomace/amarone] Valpolicella is in the province of Verona, within the large Veneto region.
[src:pomace/amarone] In Italian, the name *Amarone* literally means 'Great Bitter'; originally, this was to distinguish it from the Recioto produced in the same region, which is sweeter in taste.
[src:pomace/amarone] Notable wines have been produced in Valpolicella since ancient times, but the Verona wine was not marketed as Amarone before 1953.
[src:pomace/amarone] It is believed that the label Amarone was coined by Adelino Lucchese in 1936.
[src:pomace/amarone] The wine was assigned *denominazione di origine controllata* (DOC) status in December 1990.
[src:pomace/amarone] On 4 December 2009, Amarone and Recioto della Valpolicella were promoted to the status of *denominazione di origine controllata e garantita* (DOCG).
[src:pomace/amarone] Total production for sale (including Recioto) in 2008 was 8.57 million bottles.
[src:pomace/amarone] Grapes are harvested ripe in the first two weeks of October, by carefully choosing bunches having fruits not too close to each other, to let the air flow.
[src:pomace/amarone] Grapes are allowed to dry, traditionally on bamboo racks (**arele** in local dialect) but more commonly in plastic or wooden crates.
[src:pomace/amarone] This process is called **appassimento** or **rasinate** (to dry and shrivel) in Italian.
[src:pomace/amarone] This concentrates the remaining sugars and flavours thanks to the water evaporation and is similar to the production of French *vin de paille*.
[src:pomace/amarone] The pomace left over from pressing off the Amarone is used in the production of *ripasso* Valpolicellas.
[src:pomace/amarone] Modern Amarone is produced in special drying chambers under controlled conditions.
[src:pomace/amarone] This approach minimizes the amount of handling of the grapes and helps prevent the onset of *Botrytis cinerea*.
[src:pomace/amarone] In Amarone, the quality of the grape skin is a primary concern, as that component brings the tannins, color, and intensity of flavor to the wine.
[src:pomace/amarone] The process of desiccation not only concentrates the juices within the grape, but also increases the skin contact of the grapes.
[src:pomace/amarone] The drying process creates a polymerization of the tannins in the skin that contributes to the overall balance of the finished wine.
[src:pomace/amarone] Typically, the length of the drying process is 120 days, but varies according to producer and the quality of the harvest.
[src:pomace/amarone] The most evident consequence of this process is the loss of weight: 35 to 45% for Corvina grapes, 30 to 40% for Molinara, and 27 to 40% for Rondinella.
[src:pomace/amarone] Following the drying process that is completed during the end of January or beginning of February, the grapes are crushed and go through a dry, low temperature fermentation process that may last up to 30 or 50 days.
[src:pomace/amarone] The reduced water content can slow down the fermentation process, increasing the risk of spoilage and potential wine faults, such as high volatile acidity.
[src:pomace/amarone] After fermentation, the wine must undergo a period of ageing of at least 2 years (calculated from 1 January of the year following the harvest).
[src:pomace/amarone] The ageing process takes place in wooden barrels, traditionally in big oak casks, but tonneaux (500 lt) or barriques (225 lt) made of either French or Slavonian oak can be used.
[src:pomace/amarone] If fermentation is stopped early, the resulting wine will contain residual sugar (more than 4 grams of sugar per litre) and produce a sweeter wine known as Recioto della Valpolicella.
[src:pomace/amarone] Recioto was the traditional wine produced according to this method, and originally, Amarone was Recioto wines that had fermented for too long.
[src:pomace/amarone] Unlike Amarone, Recioto della Valpolicella may be used to produce a sparkling wine.
[src:pomace/amarone] *Ripasso* is an Italian wine produced when the partially-aged Valpolicella is contacted with the pomace of the Amarone.
[src:pomace/amarone] Typically, this will take place in the spring following the harvest.
[src:pomace/amarone] The resulting wine is more tannic, with a deeper color, and having more alcohol and more extract.
[src:pomace/amarone] The word *ripasso* designates both the winemaking technique and the wine, and usually is found on a wine label.
[src:pomace/amarone] The final result is a very ripe, raisiny, full-bodied wine with very little acid.
[src:pomace/amarone] Alcohol content easily surpasses 15% (the legal minimum is 14%) and the resulting wine is rarely released until five years after the vintage, even though this is not a legal requirement.
[src:pomace/amarone] The labor-intensive process of producing this wine poses significant risk for the development of various wine faults.
[src:pomace/amarone] Wet and rainy weather during harvest may cause the grapes to rot before drying out, requiring winemakers to be diligent in removing rotted bunches that can cause moldy flavors in the wine.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Anaerobic digestion reduces sludge volume and pathogen content while generating methane-rich biogas that can be used for renewable energy production.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] The liquid remainder, digestate can be further treated and, in some cases, beneficially reused.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Anaerobic digestion occurs naturally in some soils and in lake and oceanic basin sediments, where it is usually referred to as "anaerobic activity".
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] This is the source of marsh gas methane as discovered by Alessandro Volta in 1776.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] The digestion process begins with bacterial hydrolysis of the input materials.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Insoluble organic polymers, such as carbohydrates, are broken down to soluble derivatives that become available for other bacteria.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Acidogenic bacteria then convert the sugars and amino acids into carbon dioxide, hydrogen, ammonia, and organic acids.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] In acetogenesis, bacteria convert these resulting organic acids into acetic acid, along with additional ammonia, hydrogen, and carbon dioxide amongst other compounds.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Finally, methanogens convert these products to methane and carbon dioxide.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] The methanogenic archaea populations play an indispensable role in anaerobic wastewater treatments.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Anaerobic digestion is used as part of the process to treat biodegradable waste and sewage sludge.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] As part of an integrated waste management system, anaerobic digestion reduces the emission of landfill gas into the atmosphere.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Anaerobic digesters can also be fed with purpose-grown energy crops, such as maize.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Anaerobic digestion is widely used as a source of renewable energy.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] The process produces a biogas, consisting of methane, carbon dioxide, and traces of other 'contaminant' gases.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] This biogas can be used directly as fuel, in combined heat and power gas engines or upgraded to natural gas-quality biomethane.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] The nutrient-rich digestate also produced can be used as fertilizer.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Many microorganisms affect anaerobic digestion, including acetic acid-forming bacteria (acetogens) and methane-forming archaea (methanogens).
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] These organisms promote a number of chemical processes in converting the biomass to biogas.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Gaseous oxygen is excluded from the reactions by physical containment.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Anaerobes utilize electron acceptors from sources other than oxygen gas.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] These acceptors can be the organic material itself or may be supplied by inorganic oxides from within the input material.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] When the oxygen source in an anaerobic system is derived from the organic material itself, the 'intermediate' end products are primarily alcohols, aldehydes, and organic acids, plus carbon dioxide.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] In the presence of specialised methanogens, the intermediates are converted to the 'final' end products of methane, carbon dioxide, and trace levels of hydrogen sulfide.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] In an anaerobic system, the majority of the chemical energy contained within the starting material is released by methanogenic archaea as methane.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Populations of anaerobic microorganisms typically take a significant period of time to establish themselves to be fully effective.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Therefore, common practice is to introduce anaerobic microorganisms from materials with existing populations, a process known as "seeding" the digesters, typically accomplished with the addition of sewage sludge or cattle slurry.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] The four key stages of anaerobic digestion involve hydrolysis, acidogenesis, acetogenesis and methanogenesis.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] The overall process can be described by the chemical reaction, where organic material such as glucose is biochemically digested into carbon dioxide (CO2) and methane (CH4) by the anaerobic microorganisms.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] In most cases, biomass is made up of large organic polymers.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] For the bacteria in anaerobic digesters to access the energy potential of the material, these chains must first be broken down into their smaller constituent parts.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] These constituent parts, or monomers, such as sugars, are readily available to other bacteria.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] The process of breaking these chains and dissolving the smaller molecules into solution is called hydrolysis.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Therefore, hydrolysis of these high-molecular-weight polymeric components is the necessary first step in anaerobic digestion.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Acetate and hydrogen produced in the first stages can be used directly by methanogens.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] into compounds that can be directly used by methanogens.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] results in further breakdown of the remaining components by acidogenic (fermentative) bacteria.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Here, simple molecules created through the acidogenesis phase are further digested by acetogens to produce largely acetic acid, as well as carbon dioxide and hydrogen.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Here, methanogens use the intermediate products of the preceding stages and convert them into methane, carbon dioxide, and water.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] These components make up the majority of the biogas emitted from the system.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Methanogenesis is sensitive to both high and low pHs and occurs between pH 6.5 and pH 8.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] The remaining, indigestible material the microbes cannot use and any dead bacterial remains constitute the digestate.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Process performance depends on several operational parameters, including temperature (mesophilic conditions at approximately 35–37 °C or thermophilic conditions at 50–55 °C), organic loading rate (OLR), pH (typically maintained between 6.8 and 7.2), and solids retention time (SRT).
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Proper control of these parameters is essential to prevent process instability and volatile fatty acid accumulation.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Anaerobic digesters can be designed and engineered to operate using a number of different configurations and can be categorized into batch vs. continuous process mode, mesophilic vs. thermophilic temperature conditions, high vs. low portion of solids, and single stage vs. multistage processes.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Higher heat energy is required in a thermophilic system compared to a mesophilic system, but the thermophilic system requires much less time and has a larger gas output capacity and higher methane gas content, so one has to consider that trade-off carefully.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] For solids content, low will handle up to 15% solid content.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Above this level is considered high solids content and can also be known as dry digestion.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] In a single stage process, one reactor houses the four anaerobic digestion steps.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] A multistage process utilizes two or more reactors for digestion to separate the methanogenesis and hydrolysis phases.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Anaerobic digestion can be performed as a batch process or a continuous process.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] In a batch system, biomass is added to the reactor at the start of the process.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] The reactor is then sealed for the duration of the process.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] In its simplest form batch processing needs inoculation with already processed material to start the anaerobic digestion.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] In a typical scenario, biogas production will be formed with a normal distribution pattern over time.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Operators can use this fact to determine when they believe the process of digestion of the organic matter has completed.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] There can be severe odour issues if a batch reactor is opened and emptied before the process is well completed.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] A more advanced type of batch approach has limited the odour issues by integrating anaerobic digestion with in-vessel composting.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] In this approach inoculation takes place through the use of recirculated degasified percolate.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] After anaerobic digestion has completed, the biomass is kept in the reactor which is then used for in-vessel composting before it is opened As the batch digestion is simple and requires less equipment and lower levels of design work, it is typically a cheaper form of digestion.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Using more than one batch reactor at a plant can ensure constant production of biogas.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] In continuous digestion processes, organic matter is constantly added (continuous complete mixed) or added in stages to the reactor (continuous plug flow; first in – first out).
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Here, the end products are constantly or periodically removed, resulting in constant production of biogas.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] A single or multiple digesters in sequence may be used.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Examples of this form of anaerobic digestion include continuous stirred-tank reactors, upflow anaerobic sludge blankets, expanded granular sludge beds, and internal circulation reactors.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] A limit case has been reached in Bolivia, with anaerobic digestion in temperature working conditions of less than 10 °C.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] The anaerobic process is very slow, taking more than three times the normal mesophilic time process.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] In experimental work at University of Alaska Fairbanks, a 1,000-litre digester using psychrophiles harvested from "mud from a frozen lake in Alaska" has produced 200–300 litres of methane per day, about 20 to 30% of the output from digesters in warmer climates.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Mesophilic species outnumber thermophiles, and they are also more tolerant to changes in environmental conditions than thermophiles.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Mesophilic systems are, therefore, considered to be more stable than thermophilic digestion systems.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] In contrast, while thermophilic digestion systems are considered less stable, their energy input is higher, with more biogas being removed from the organic matter in an equal amount of time.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] The increased temperatures facilitate faster reaction rates, and thus faster gas yields.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Operation at higher temperatures facilitates greater pathogen reduction of the digestate.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] In countries where legislation, such as the Animal By-Products Regulations in the European Union, requires digestate to meet certain levels of pathogen reduction there may be a benefit to using thermophilic temperatures instead of mesophilic.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Additional pre-treatment can be used to reduce the necessary retention time to produce biogas.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] For example, certain processes shred the substrates to increase the surface area or use a thermal pretreatment stage (such as pasteurisation) to significantly enhance the biogas output.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] The pasteurisation process can also be used to reduce the pathogenic concentration in the digestate, leaving the anaerobic digester.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Pasteurisation may be achieved by heat treatment combined with maceration of the solids.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] High solids (dry) digesters are designed to process materials with a solids content between 25 and 40%.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Unlike wet digesters that process pumpable slurries, high solids (dry – stackable substrate) digesters are designed to process solid substrates without the addition of water.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] The primary styles of dry digesters are continuous vertical plug flow and batch tunnel horizontal digesters.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Continuous vertical plug flow digesters are upright, cylindrical tanks where feedstock is continuously fed into the top of the digester, and flows downward by gravity during digestion.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] In batch tunnel digesters, the feedstock is deposited in tunnel-like chambers with a gas-tight door.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Neither approach has mixing inside the digester.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] The amount of pretreatment, such as contaminant removal, depends both upon the nature of the waste streams being processed and the desired quality of the digestate.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Size reduction (grinding) is beneficial in continuous vertical systems, as it accelerates digestion, while batch systems avoid grinding and instead require structure (e.g. yard waste) to reduce compaction of the stacked pile.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Continuous vertical dry digesters have a smaller footprint due to the shorter effective retention time and vertical design.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Wet digesters can be designed to operate in either a high-solids content, with a total suspended solids (TSS) concentration greater than ~20%, or a low-solids concentration less than ~15%.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] High solids (wet) digesters process a thick slurry that requires more energy input to move and process the feedstock.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] The thickness of the material may also lead to associated problems with abrasion.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] High solids digesters will typically have a lower land requirement due to the lower volumes associated with the moisture.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] High solids digesters also require correction of conventional performance calculations (e.g. gas production, retention time, kinetics, etc.) originally based on very dilute sewage digestion concepts, since larger fractions of the feedstock mass are potentially convertible to biogas.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Low solids (wet) digesters can transport material through the system using standard pumps that require significantly lower energy input.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Low solids digesters require a larger amount of land than high solids due to the increased volumes associated with the increased liquid-to-feedstock ratio of the digesters.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] There are benefits associated with operation in a liquid environment, as it enables more thorough circulation of materials and contact between the bacteria and their food.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] This enables the bacteria to more readily access the substances on which they are feeding, and increases the rate of gas production.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Digestion systems can be configured with different levels of complexity.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] In a **single-stage digestion system** (one-stage), all of the biological reactions occur within a single, sealed reactor or holding tank.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Using a single stage reduces construction costs, but results in less control of the reactions occurring within the system.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Acidogenic bacteria, through the production of acids, reduce the pH of the tank.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Methanogenic archaea, as outlined earlier, operate in a strictly defined pH range.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Therefore, the biological reactions of the different species in a single-stage reactor can be in direct competition with each other.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Another one-stage reaction system is an anaerobic lagoon.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] These lagoons are pond-like, earthen basins used for the treatment and long-term storage of manures.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Here the anaerobic reactions are contained within the natural anaerobic sludge contained in the pool.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] In a **two-stage digestion system** (multistage), different digestion vessels are optimised to bring maximum control over the bacterial communities living within the digesters.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Acidogenic bacteria produce organic acids and more quickly grow and reproduce than methanogenic archaea.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Methanogenic archaea require stable pH and temperature to optimise their performance.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Under typical circumstances, hydrolysis, acetogenesis, and acidogenesis occur within the first reaction vessel.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] The organic material is then heated to the required operational temperature (either mesophilic or thermophilic) prior to being pumped into a methanogenic reactor.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] The initial hydrolysis or acidogenesis tanks prior to the methanogenic reactor can provide a buffer to the rate at which feedstock is added.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Some European countries require a degree of elevated heat treatment to kill harmful bacteria in the input waste.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] In this instance, there may be a pasteurisation or sterilisation stage prior to digestion or between the two digestion tanks.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Notably, it is not possible to completely isolate the different reaction phases, and often some biogas is produced in the hydrolysis or acidogenesis tanks.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] The residence time in a digester varies with the amount and type of feed material, and with the configuration of the digestion system.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] In a typical two-stage mesophilic digestion, residence time varies between 15 and 40 days, while for a single-stage thermophilic digestion, residence times is normally faster and takes around 14 days.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] The plug-flow nature of some of these systems will mean the full degradation of the material may not have been realised in this timescale.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] In this event, digestate exiting the system will be darker in colour and will typically have more odour.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] In the case of an upflow anaerobic sludge blanket digestion (UASB), hydraulic residence times can be as short as 1 hour to 1 day, and solid retention times can be up to 90 days.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] In this manner, a UASB system is able to separate solids and hydraulic retention times with the use of a sludge blanket.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Continuous digesters have mechanical or hydraulic devices, depending on the level of solids in the material, to mix the contents, enabling the bacteria and the food to be in contact.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] They also allow excess material to be continuously extracted to maintain a reasonably constant volume within the digestion tanks.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] A recent development in anaerobic reactor design is High-pressure anaerobic digestion (HPAD) also referred to an Autogenerative High Pressure Digestion (AHPD).
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] This technique produces a biogas with an elevated methane content.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] The produced carbon dioxide in biogas dissolves more into the water phase under pressure than methane does.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Hence the produced biogas is richer in methane.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Research at the University of Groningen demonstrated that the bacterial community changes in composition under the influence of pressure.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Individual bacteria species have their optimum circumstances in which they grow and replicate the fastest.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Commonly known are pH, temperature, salinity etc. but pressure is also one of them.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Some species have adapted to life in the deep oceans where pressure is much higher than at sea level.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] This makes it possible in similar vein as other process parameters such as Temperature, Retention Time, pH to influence the anaerobic digestion process.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] in Germany, 2007 - the green, inflatable biogas holder is shown on top of the digester.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] The anaerobic digestion process can be inhibited by several compounds, affecting one or more of the bacterial groups responsible for the different organic matter degradation steps.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] The degree of the inhibition depends, among other factors, on the concentration of the inhibitor in the digester.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Potential inhibitors are ammonia, sulfide, light metal ions (Na, K, Mg, Ca, Al), heavy metals, some organics (chlorophenols, halogenated aliphatics, N-substituted aromatics, long chain fatty acids), etc.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Total ammonia nitrogen (TAN) has been shown to inhibit production of methane.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Furthermore, it destabilises the microbial community, impacting the synthesis of acetic acid.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Acetic acid is one of the driving forces in methane production.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] At an excess of 5000 mg/L TAN, pH adjustment is needed to keep the reaction stable.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] A TAN concentration above 1700– 1800 mg/L inhibits methane production and yield decreases at greater TAN concentrations.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] High TAN concentrations cause the reaction to turn acidic and lead to a domino effect of inhibition.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Total ammonia nitrogen is the combination of free ammonia and ionized ammonia.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] TAN is produced through degrading material high in nitrogen, typically proteins and will naturally build in anaerobic digestion.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] This is depending on the organic feed stock fed to the system.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] In typical wastewater treatment practices, TAN reduction is done with via nitrification.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Nitrification is an aerobic process where TAN is consumed by aerobic heterotrophic bacteria.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] These bacteria release nitrate and nitrite which are later converted to nitrogen gas through the denitrification process.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Hydrolysis and acidogenesis can also be impacted by TAN concentration.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] In mesophilic conditions, inhibition for hydrolysis was found to occur at 5500 mg/L TAN, while acidogenesis inhibition occurs at 6500 mg/L TAN.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] The most important initial issue when considering the application of anaerobic digestion systems is the feedstock to the process.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Almost any organic material can be processed with anaerobic digestion however, if biogas production is the aim, the level of putrescibility is the key factor in its successful application.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] The more putrescible (digestible) the material, the higher the gas yields possible from the system.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Feedstocks can include biodegradable waste materials, such as waste paper, grass clippings, leftover food, sewage, and animal waste.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Woody wastes are the exception, because they are largely unaffected by digestion, as most anaerobes are unable to degrade lignin.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Xylophagous anaerobes (lignin consumers) or high temperature pretreatment, such as pyrolysis, can be used to break lignin down.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Anaerobic digesters can also be fed with specially grown energy crops, such as silage, for dedicated biogas production.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] In Germany and continental Europe, these facilities are referred to as "biogas" plants.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] A codigestion or cofermentation plant is typically an agricultural anaerobic digester that accepts two or more input materials for simultaneous digestion.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] The length of time required for anaerobic digestion depends on the chemical complexity of the material.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Material rich in easily digestible sugars breaks down quickly, whereas intact lignocellulosic material rich in cellulose and hemicellulose polymers can take much longer to break down.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Anaerobic microorganisms are generally unable to break down lignin, the recalcitrant aromatic component of biomass.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Anaerobic digesters were originally designed for operation using sewage sludge and manures.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Sewage and manure are not, however, the material with the most potential for anaerobic digestion, as the biodegradable material has already had much of the energy content taken out by the animals that produced it.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Therefore, many digesters operate with codigestion of two or more types of feedstock.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Digesters processing dedicated energy crops can achieve high levels of degradation and biogas production.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] A second consideration related to the feedstock is moisture content.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Drier, stackable substrates, such as food and yard waste, are suitable for digestion in tunnel-like chambers.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Tunnel-style systems typically have near-zero wastewater discharge, as well, so this style of system has advantages where the discharge of digester liquids are a liability.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] The wetter the material, the more suitable it will be to handling with standard pumps instead of energy-intensive concrete pumps and physical means of movement.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Also, the wetter the material, the more volume and area it takes up relative to the levels of gas produced.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] The moisture content of the target feedstock will also affect what type of system is applied to its treatment.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] To use a high-solids anaerobic digester for dilute feedstocks, bulking agents, such as compost, should be applied to increase the solids content of the input material.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Another key consideration is the carbon:nitrogen ratio of the input material.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] This ratio is the balance of food a microbe requires to grow; the optimal C:N ratio is 20–30:1.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Excess N can lead to ammonia inhibition of digestion.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] The level of contamination of the feedstock material is a key consideration when using wet digestion or plug-flow digestion.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] If the feedstock to the digesters has significant levels of physical contaminants, such as plastic, glass, or metals, then processing to remove the contaminants will be required for the material to be used.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] If it is not removed, then the digesters can be blocked and will not function efficiently.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] This contamination issue does not occur with dry digestion or solid-state anaerobic digestion (SSAD) plants, since SSAD handles dry, stackable biomass with a high percentage of solids (40-60%) in gas-tight chambers called fermenter boxes.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] It is with this understanding that mechanical biological treatment plants are designed.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] The higher the level of pretreatment a feedstock requires, the more processing machinery will be required, and, hence, the project will have higher capital costs.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] After sorting or screening to remove any physical contaminants from the feedstock, the material is often shredded, minced, and mechanically or hydraulically pulped to increase the surface area available to microbes in the digesters and, hence, increase the speed of digestion.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] The maceration of solids can be achieved by using a chopper pump to transfer the feedstock material into the airtight digester, where anaerobic treatment takes place.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Substrate composition is a major factor in determining the methane yield and methane production rates from the digestion of biomass.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Techniques to determine the compositional characteristics of the feedstock are available, while parameters such as solids, elemental, and organic analyses are important for digester design and operation.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Methane yield can be estimated from the elemental composition of substrate along with an estimate of its degradability (the fraction of the substrate that is converted to biogas in a reactor).
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Direct measurements of biomethanation potential are also made using gas evolution or more recent gravimetric assays.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Anaerobic digestion is particularly suited to organic material, and is commonly used for industrial effluent, wastewater and sewage sludge treatment.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Anaerobic digestion, a simple process, can greatly reduce the amount of organic matter which might otherwise be destined to be dumped at sea, dumped in landfills, or burnt in incinerators.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Pressure from environmentally related legislation on solid waste disposal methods in developed countries has increased the application of anaerobic digestion as a process for reducing waste volumes and generating useful byproducts.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] It may either be used to process the source-separated fraction of municipal waste or alternatively combined with mechanical sorting systems, to process residual mixed municipal waste.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] These facilities are called mechanical biological treatment plants.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] If the putrescible waste processed in anaerobic digesters were disposed of in a landfill, it would break down naturally and often anaerobically.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] In this case, the gas will eventually escape into the atmosphere.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] As methane is about 20 times more potent as a greenhouse gas than carbon dioxide, this has significant negative environmental effects.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] In countries that collect household waste, the use of local anaerobic digestion facilities can help to reduce the amount of waste that requires transportation to centralized landfill sites or incineration facilities.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] This reduced burden on transportation reduces carbon emissions from the collection vehicles.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] If localized anaerobic digestion facilities are embedded within an electrical distribution network, they can help reduce the electrical losses associated with transporting electricity over a national grid.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Anaerobic digestion can be used for the remediation of sludge polluted with PFAS.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] A 2024 study has shown that anaerobic digestion, combined with adsorption in activated carbon and voltage application can remove up to 61% of PFAS from sewage sludge.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] In developing countries, simple home and farm-based anaerobic digestion systems offer the potential for low-cost energy for cooking and lighting.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] From 1975, China and India have both had large, government-backed schemes for adaptation of small biogas plants for use in the household for cooking and lighting.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] At present, projects for anaerobic digestion in the developing world can gain financial support through the United Nations Clean Development Mechanism if they are able to show they provide reduced carbon emissions.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Methane and power produced in anaerobic digestion facilities can be used to replace energy derived from fossil fuels, and hence reduce emissions of greenhouse gases, because the carbon in biodegradable material is part of a carbon cycle.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] The carbon released into the atmosphere from the combustion of biogas has been removed by plants for them to grow in the recent past, usually within the last decade, but more typically within the last growing season.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] If the plants are regrown, taking the carbon out of the atmosphere once more, the system will be carbon neutral.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] In contrast, carbon in fossil fuels has been sequestered in the earth for many millions of years, the combustion of which increases the overall levels of carbon dioxide in the atmosphere.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Power generation through anaerobic digesters is best suited to large-scale operations, rather than small farms, as large operations have the volume of manure that is able to make the systems financially viable.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Biogas from sewage sludge treatment is sometimes used to run a gas engine to produce electrical power, some or all of which can be used to run the sewage works.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Some waste heat from the engine is then used to heat the digester.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] The waste heat is, in general, enough to heat the digester to the required temperatures.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] The power potential from sewage works is limited – in the UK, there are about 80 MW total of such generation, with the potential to increase to 150 MW, which is insignificant compared to the average power demand in the UK of about 35,000 MW.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] The scope for biogas generation from nonsewage waste biological matter – energy crops, food waste, abattoir waste, etc. - is much higher, estimated to be capable of about 3,000 MW.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Farm biogas plants using animal waste and energy crops are expected to contribute to reducing CO2 emissions and strengthen the grid, while providing UK farmers with additional revenues.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Some countries offer incentives in the form of, for example, feed-in tariffs for feeding electricity onto the power grid to subsidize green energy production.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] In Oakland, California at the East Bay Municipal Utility District's main wastewater treatment plant (EBMUD), food waste is currently codigested with primary and secondary municipal wastewater solids and other high-strength wastes.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Compared to municipal wastewater solids digestion alone, food waste codigestion has many benefits.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Anaerobic digestion of food waste pulp from the EBMUD food waste process provides a higher normalized energy benefit, compared to municipal wastewater solids: 730 to 1,300 kWh per dry ton of food waste applied compared to 560 to 940 kWh per dry ton of municipal wastewater solids applied.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] The methane component of biogas can be concentrated through upgrading into biomethane.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Biomethane (also known as renewable natural gas) can be injected into the natural gas grid.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] The upgrading process removes contaminants such as hydrogen sulphide and siloxanes, as well as non-methane gas constituents, chiefly carbon dioxide.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Several technologies are available for this purpose, the most widely implemented being pressure swing adsorption (PSA), water or amine scrubbing (absorption processes) and membrane separation.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] After upgrading with the above-mentioned technologies, biomethane can be compressed into compressed natural gas and used in natural gas vehicles.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Use of natural gas vehicles is very extensive in Sweden, where over 38,600 gas vehicles exist, and 60% of the CNG supply is biomethane generated in anaerobic digestion plants.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] The solid, fibrous component of the digested material can be used as a soil conditioner to increase the organic content of soils.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Digester liquor can be used as a fertiliser to supply vital nutrients to soils instead of chemical fertilisers that require large amounts of energy to produce and transport.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] The use of manufactured fertilisers is, therefore, more carbon-intensive than the use of anaerobic digester liquor fertiliser.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] In countries such as Spain, where many soils are organically depleted, the markets for the digested solids can be equally as important as the biogas.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Anaerobic digestion can be used at a small scale to produce gas for cooking.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] The organic waste like fallen leaves, kitchen waste, food waste etc. are fed into a crusher unit, where it is mixed with a small amount of water.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] The mixture is then fed into the anaerobic digester, where the archaea decomposes it to produce cooking gas.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] A 2 cubic meter anaerobic digester can produce 2 cubic meters of cooking gas.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] The three principal products of anaerobic digestion are biogas, digestate, and water.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Biogas is the ultimate waste product of the microbes feeding off the input biodegradable feedstock and is mostly methane and carbon dioxide, with a small amount of hydrogen (H 2), water vapor (H 2O, amount depending on temperature), and trace hydrogen sulfide (H 2S).
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Most of the biogas is produced during the middle of the digestion, after the bacterial population has grown, and tapers off as the putrescible material is exhausted.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] The gas is normally stored on top of the digester in an inflatable gas bubble or extracted and stored next to the facility in a gas holder.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] The methane in biogas can be burned to produce both heat and electricity, usually with a reciprocating engine or microturbine often in a cogeneration arrangement where the electricity and waste heat generated are used to warm the digesters or to heat buildings.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Excess electricity can be sold to suppliers or put into the local grid.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Electricity produced by anaerobic digesters is considered to be renewable energy and may attract subsidies.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Biogas does not contribute to increasing atmospheric carbon dioxide concentrations because the gas is not released directly into the atmosphere and the carbon dioxide comes from an organic source with a short carbon cycle.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Biogas may require treatment or 'scrubbing' to refine it for use as a fuel.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Hydrogen sulfide, a toxic product formed from sulfates in the feedstock, is released as a trace component of the biogas.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] National environmental enforcement agencies, such as the U.S.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Alternatively, the addition of ferrous chloride FeCl2 to the digestion tanks inhibits hydrogen sulfide production.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Volatile siloxanes can also contaminate the biogas; such compounds are frequently found in household waste and wastewater.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] In digestion facilities accepting these materials as a component of the feedstock, low-molecular-weight siloxanes volatilise into biogas.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] When this gas is combusted in a gas engine, turbine, or boiler, siloxanes are converted into silicon dioxide (SiO2), which deposits internally in the machine, increasing wear and tear.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Practical and cost-effective technologies to remove siloxanes and other biogas contaminants are available at the present time.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] In certain applications, *in situ* treatment can be used to increase the methane purity by reducing the offgas carbon dioxide content, purging the majority of it in a secondary reactor.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] In countries such as Switzerland, Germany, and Sweden, the methane in the biogas may be compressed for it to be used as a vehicle transportation fuel or input directly into the gas mains.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] In countries where the driver for the use of anaerobic digestion are renewable electricity subsidies, this route of treatment is less likely, as energy is required in this processing stage and reduces the overall levels available to sell.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Digestate is the non-gaseous product of the digesters.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] It consists of remnants of the original input material to the digesters that the microbes cannot use and the mineralised remains of the dead bacteria from within the digesters.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] The acidogenic and methanogenic steps each produce a digestate product, which are fibrous and liquid respectively.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] In two-stage systems, different forms of digestate come from different digestion tanks.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] In single-stage digestion systems, the two fractions appear combined into a sludge and, if desired, can be separated by further processing.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] The acidogenic digestate is a stable, organic, fiborous material consisting largely of lignin and cellulose, but also of a variety of mineral components in a matrix of dead bacterial cells; some plastic may be present.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] The material resembles domestic compost and can be used as such.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] It can also be used as a lignocellulosic biomass to make low-grade building products such as fibreboard. or as feedstock for ethanol production.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] The methanogenic digestate is a liquid rich in plant nutrients (nitrogen as ammoniums and potassium), which can be used as a fertiliser, depending on the quality of the material being digested.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Levels of potentially toxic elements (PTEs) should be chemically assessed.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] This will depend upon the quality of the original feedstock.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] In the case of most clean and source-separated biodegradable waste streams, the levels of PTEs will be low.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] In the case of wastes originating from industry, the levels of PTEs may be higher and will need to be taken into consideration when determining a suitable end use for the material.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Acidogenic digestate typically contains biopolymers, such as lignin, that cannot be broken down by the anaerobic microorganisms.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Methanogenic digestate may contain ammonia at phytotoxic levels and may hamper the growth of plants if it is used as a soil-improving material.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] For these two reasons, a maturation or composting stage may be employed after digestion.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Lignin and other materials are available for degradation by aerobic microorganisms such as fungi.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] During maturation, ammonia is oxidized into nitrates which improves the fertility of the material as a soil amendment.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] In addition, composting leads to significant mass loss (primarily through evaporation) reducing the amount of material that needs to be trucked off-site.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Composting is often used in dry digesters, as wet digesters require bulking with wood products or other material to be compostable.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] As most digesters are unable to degrade compostable packaging, secondary composting is required for this sort of packaging to be processed in an anaerobic digester.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] The final output from anaerobic digestion systems is water, which originates both from the moisture content of the original waste that was treated and water produced during the microbial reactions in the digestion systems.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] This water may be released from the dewatering of the digestate or may be implicitly separate from the digestate.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] The wastewater exiting the anaerobic digestion facility will typically have elevated levels of biochemical oxygen demand (BOD) and chemical oxygen demand (COD).
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] These measures of the reactivity of the effluent indicate an ability to pollute.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Some of this material is termed 'hard COD', meaning it cannot be accessed by the anaerobic bacteria for conversion into biogas.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] If this effluent were put directly into watercourses, it would negatively affect them by causing eutrophication.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] As such, further treatment of the wastewater is often required.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] This treatment will typically be an oxidation stage wherein air is passed through the water in a sequencing batch reactors or reverse osmosis unit.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Reported scientific interest in the manufacturing of gas produced by the natural decomposition of organic matter dates from the 17th century, when Robert Boyle (1627–1691) and Stephen Hales (1677–1761) noted that disturbing the sediment of streams and lakes released flammable gas.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] In 1778, the Italian physicist Alessandro Volta (1745–1827), the father of electrochemistry, scientifically identified that gas as methane.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] In 1808 Sir Humphry Davy proved the presence of methane in the gases produced by cattle manure.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] The first known anaerobic digester was built in 1859 at a leper colony in Bombay in India.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] In 1895, the technology was developed in Exeter, England, where a septic tank was used to generate gas for the sewer gas destructor lamp, a type of gas lighting.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Also in England, in 1904, the first dual-purpose tank for both sedimentation and sludge treatment was installed in Hampton, London.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] By the early 20th century, anaerobic digestion systems began to resemble the technology as it appears today.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] In 1906, Karl Imhoff created the Imhoff tank; an early form of anaerobic digester and model wastewater treatment system throughout the early 20th century.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] After 1920, closed tank systems began to replace the previously common use of anaerobic lagoons – covered earthen basins used to treat volatile solids.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Research on anaerobic digestion began in earnest in the 1930s.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Around the time of World War I, production from biofuels slowed as petroleum production increased and its uses were identified.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] While fuel shortages during World War II re-popularized anaerobic digestion, interest in the technology decreased again after the war ended.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Similarly, the 1970s energy crisis sparked interest in anaerobic digestion.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] During the 1970s energy crisis, interest in small-scale and rural anaerobic digestion systems increased internationally.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Ram Bux Singh developed and promoted early gobar gas (biogas) plants and contributed to the dissemination of anaerobic digestion technology for rural energy applications.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] His work was also referenced in publications such as *Mother Earth News*, which described him as “perhaps the father of methane development in the United States” during early biogas experimentation efforts.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] In addition to high energy prices, factors affecting the adoption of anaerobic digestion systems include receptivity to innovation, pollution penalties, policy incentives, and the availability of subsidies and funding opportunities.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Today, anaerobic digesters are commonly found alongside farms to reduce nitrogen run-off from manure, or wastewater treatment facilities to reduce the costs of sludge disposal.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Agricultural anaerobic digestion for energy production has become most popular in Germany, where there were 8,625 digesters in 2014.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] In the United Kingdom, there were 259 facilities by 2014, and 500 projects planned to become operational by 2019.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] In the United States, there were 191 operational plants across 34 states in 2012.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Policy may explain why adoption rates are so different across these countries.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Feed-in tariffs in Germany were enacted in 1991, also known as FIT, providing long-term contracts compensating investments in renewable energy generation.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Consequently, between 1991 and 1998 the number of anaerobic digester plants in Germany grew from 20 to 517.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] In the late 1990s, energy prices in Germany varied and investors became unsure of the market's potential.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] The German government responded by amending FIT four times between 2000 and 2011, increasing tariffs and improving the profitability of anaerobic digestion, and resulting in reliable returns for biogas production and continued high adoption rates across the country.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Anaerobic digesters have caused fish kills (e.g.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] River Mole, Devon, River Teifi, Afon Llynfi, and loss of human life (e.g.
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Fortunately, according to one source, 'less than a dozen of them had consequences on humans'- for example, the incident at Rhadereistedt, Germany (4 dead).
[src:pomace/anaerobic-digesters] Safety analyses have included a 2016 study compiled a database of 169 accidents involving ADs.
[src:pomace/ancient-greek-wine] The influence of wine in ancient Greece helped ancient Greece trade with neighboring countries and regions.
[src:pomace/ancient-greek-wine] Many mannerisms and cultural aspects were associated with wine.
[src:pomace/ancient-greek-wine] It led to great change in Ancient Greece as well.
[src:pomace/ancient-greek-wine] The ancient Greeks pioneered new methods of viticulture and wine production that they shared with early winemaking communities in what are now France, Italy, Austria and Russia, as well as others, through trade and colonization.
[src:pomace/ancient-greek-wine] Along the way, they markedly influenced the ancient European winemaking cultures of the Celts, Etruscans, Scythians and ultimately the Romans.
[src:pomace/ancient-greek-wine] Viticulture has existed in Greece since the late Neolithic period, with domestic cultivation becoming widespread by the early Bronze Age.
[src:pomace/ancient-greek-wine] Through trade with ancient Egypt, the Minoan civilization on Crete was introduced to Egyptian winemaking methods, an influence most likely imparted to Mycenaean Greece.
[src:pomace/ancient-greek-wine] The Minoan palaces had their associated vineyards, as Spyridon Marinatos demonstrated in excavations just south of the palace site at Archanes, and the Minoan equivalent of a *villa rustica* devoted to wine production was unearthed at Kato Zakros in 1961.
[src:pomace/ancient-greek-wine] In Minoan culture of the mid-second millennium BC, wine and the sacred bull were linked in the form of the horn-shaped drinking cups called *rhyta*; the name of Oinops (Greek: οἶνοψ, "wine-colored") is twice attested in Linear B tablets at Knossos and repeated twice in Homer.
[src:pomace/ancient-greek-wine] Along with olives and grain, grapes were an important agricultural crop vital to sustenance and community development; the ancient Greek calendar followed the course of the vintner's year.
[src:pomace/ancient-greek-wine] One of the earliest known wine presses was discovered in Palekastro in Crete, from which island the Mycenaeans are believed to have spread viticulture to others in the Aegean Sea and quite possibly to mainland Greece.
[src:pomace/ancient-greek-wine] In the Mycenaean period, wine took on greater cultural, religious and economic importance.
[src:pomace/ancient-greek-wine] Records inscribed on tablets in Linear B include details of wine, vineyards and wine merchants, as well as an early allusion to Dionysus, the Greek god of wine.
[src:pomace/ancient-greek-wine] Greeks embedded the arrival of winemaking culture in the mythologies of Dionysus and the cultural hero Aristaeus.
[src:pomace/ancient-greek-wine] Early remnants of amphoras show that the Mycenaeans actively traded wine throughout the ancient world in places such as Cyprus, Egypt, Palestine, Sicily and southern Italy.
[src:pomace/ancient-greek-wine] As the Greek city-states established colonies throughout the Mediterranean, the settlers brought grapevines with them and were active in cultivating the wild vines they encountered.
[src:pomace/ancient-greek-wine] Sicily and southern Italy formed some of the earliest colonies, as they were areas already home to an abundance of grapevines.
[src:pomace/ancient-greek-wine] The Greeks called the southern part of the Italian Peninsula Oenotria ("land of vines").
[src:pomace/ancient-greek-wine] Settlements in Massalia in southern France and along the shores of the Black Sea soon followed, with the expectation that not only would colonial wine production supply domestic needs, but also create trading opportunities to meet the demand of the nearby city-states.
[src:pomace/ancient-greek-wine] Athens itself provided a large and lucrative market for wine, with significant vineyard estates forming in the Attican region and on the island of Thasos to help satisfy demand.
[src:pomace/ancient-greek-wine] Wine historians have theorized that the Greeks may have introduced viticulture to Spain and Portugal, but competing theories suggest that the Phoenicians probably reached those areas first.
[src:pomace/ancient-greek-wine] The grape clusters, vines and wine cups that adorn Greek coins from classical times bear witness to the importance of wine to the ancient Greek economy.
[src:pomace/ancient-greek-wine] With every major trading partner, from the Crimea, Egypt, Scythia, Etruria and beyond, the Greeks traded their knowledge of viticulture and winemaking, as well the fruits of their own production.
[src:pomace/ancient-greek-wine] Millions of amphora pieces bearing the unique seals of various city-states and Aegean islands have been uncovered by archaeologists, demonstrating the scope of Greek influence.
[src:pomace/ancient-greek-wine] A shipwreck discovered off the coast of southern France included nearly 10,000 amphoras containing nearly 300,000 litres (79,000 US gal) of Greek wine, presumably destined for trade up the Rhône and Saône rivers into Gaul.
[src:pomace/ancient-greek-wine] It is estimated that the Greeks shipped nearly 10 million liters of wine into Gaul each year through Massalia.
[src:pomace/ancient-greek-wine] In 1929, the discovery of the Vix Grave in Burgundy included several artifacts demonstrating the strong ties between Greek wine traders and local Celtic villagers.
[src:pomace/ancient-greek-wine] The most notable of these was a large Greek-made krater, designed to hold over 1,000 litres (260 US gal) of wine.
[src:pomace/ancient-greek-wine] Ancient Greeks called the cultivated vine *hemeris* (Greek: ἡμερίς), after their adjective for "tame" (Greek: ἥμερος), differentiating it from its wild form.
[src:pomace/ancient-greek-wine] A massive rootstock was carved into a cult image of the Great Goddess and set up on the coast of Phrygia by the Argonauts.
[src:pomace/ancient-greek-wine] He also wrote that Laertes, father of Odysseus, had over 50 grape varieties planted in different parts of his vineyard.
[src:pomace/ancient-greek-wine] The 4th-century BC Greek writer Theophrastus left a detailed record of some Greek influences and innovations in viticulture, one of which was the study of vineyard soils and their proper match to specific grapevines.
[src:pomace/ancient-greek-wine] Another innovation was the minimization of yields for more intense concentration of flavors and quality, rather than increased quantity.
[src:pomace/ancient-greek-wine] The economics of the time favored high yields for most crops, and intentionally limiting agricultural output was exceedingly uncommon in the ancient world.
[src:pomace/ancient-greek-wine] Theophrastus also detailed the practice of using suckering and plant cuttings for new vineyard plantings.
[src:pomace/ancient-greek-wine] The Greeks also employed vine training with stacked plants for easier cultivation and harvesting, rather than let the grapevines grow untrained in bushes or up trees.
[src:pomace/ancient-greek-wine] While ampelographers have been unable to identify the exact ancestry of any current *Vitis vinifera* grape variety among those grown by the ancient Greeks, several—e.g.
[src:pomace/ancient-greek-wine] Aglianico (also known as *Helleniko*), Grechetto, and Trebbiano (also known as *Greco*)—have distinct Greek heritage.
[src:pomace/ancient-greek-wine] Not all Greek viticulture techniques were widely adopted by other wine regions.
[src:pomace/ancient-greek-wine] Some Greek vineyards used mysticism to ward off disease and bad weather.
[src:pomace/ancient-greek-wine] For example, two vineyard workers would tear a live white rooster in two, each then carrying one half around the perimeter of the vineyard in an opposite direction from the other.
[src:pomace/ancient-greek-wine] Where they met again, the carcass would be buried next to the vineyard.
[src:pomace/ancient-greek-wine] The Greeks practiced an early form of *pigeage* when grapes were ready for crushing.
[src:pomace/ancient-greek-wine] Wicker baskets filled with grapes were placed inside wooden or earthenware vats with a rope or plank above.
[src:pomace/ancient-greek-wine] Vineyard workers grasped the rope for balance to crush the grapes with their feet, occasionally to the accompaniment of a flute played in a festive manner.
[src:pomace/ancient-greek-wine] After crushing, the grapes were placed in large *pithoi*, jars where fermentation took place.
[src:pomace/ancient-greek-wine] Both Hesiod's writings and Homer's *Odyssey* include some of the earliest mentions of straw wine production: laying out freshly harvested grapes on mats to dry nearly to raisins before pressing.
[src:pomace/ancient-greek-wine] A wine made on Lesbos known as *protropon* was among the first known to be made exclusively from "free-run juice," drawn from grape clusters expressing their contents under their own weight.
[src:pomace/ancient-greek-wine] Other Greek innovations include the harvest of deliberately unripe grapes in producing a more acidic wine for blending.
[src:pomace/ancient-greek-wine] The boiling of grape must was discovered as another means of adding sweetness to the wine.
[src:pomace/ancient-greek-wine] The Greeks believed wine could also be improved by adding resin, herbs, spice, seawater, brine, oil and perfume.
[src:pomace/ancient-greek-wine] Retsina, mulled wine and vermouth are some modern examples of these practices.
[src:pomace/ancient-greek-wine] As late as the Second Council of Constantinople in 691 AD, exactly three centuries after Theodosius closed the temples, a canon was issued expressly forbidding the cries of "Dionysus!" from the wine treaders, who still were masked; it was recommended that *"Kyrie eleison"* be substituted.
[src:pomace/ancient-greek-wine] The reputation of a wine depends on the region the wine came from rather than an individual producer or vineyard.
[src:pomace/ancient-greek-wine] In the 4th century BC, the most expensive wine sold in the local agora in Athens was that from Chios, which sold for between a quarter of a drachma and 2 drachma for a chous worth—about 3 liters, or the equivalent of four standard 750 ml wine bottles today.
[src:pomace/ancient-greek-wine] Like early wine critics, Greek poets would extol the virtues of certain wines and review less favorably those not up to their standards.
[src:pomace/ancient-greek-wine] The wines most frequently cited as being of good quality were those of Chalkidike, Ismaros, Chios, Kos, Lesbos, Mende, Naxos, Peparethos (present-day Skopelos) and Thasos.
[src:pomace/ancient-greek-wine] Among individual wines lauded were two with unknown origins: Bibline and Pramnian.
[src:pomace/ancient-greek-wine] Bibline is believed to have been made in a style similar to the Phoenician wine from Byblos, highly regarded for its perfumed fragrance by Greek writers like Archestratus.
[src:pomace/ancient-greek-wine] The Greek version of the wine is thought to have originated in Thrace from a grape variety known as Bibline.
[src:pomace/ancient-greek-wine] Pramnian wine was found in several regions, most notably Lesbos but also Icaria and Smyrna (in present-day Turkey).
[src:pomace/ancient-greek-wine] It was suggested by Athenaeus that Pramnian was a generic name referring to a dark wine of good quality and aging potential.
[src:pomace/ancient-greek-wine] The earliest reference to a named wine is from the lyrical poet Alkman (7th century BC), who praises "Dénthis," a wine from the western foothills of Mount Taygetus in Messenia, as "*anthosmías*" ("smelling of flowers").
[src:pomace/ancient-greek-wine] According to wine expert Jancis Robinson, Limnio was almost certainly the *Lemnia* grape described by Aristotle as a speciality of the island of Limnos, which was probably the same as the modern-day Lemnió varietal, a red wine with a bouquet of oregano and thyme.
[src:pomace/ancient-greek-wine] If so, this makes Lemnió the oldest known varietal still in cultivation.
[src:pomace/ancient-greek-wine] The most common style of wine in ancient Greece was sweet and aromatic, though drier wines were also produced.
[src:pomace/ancient-greek-wine] Color ranged from dark, inky black to tawny to nearly clear.
[src:pomace/ancient-greek-wine] Oxidation was difficult to control, a common wine fault that meant many wines did not retain their quality beyond the next vintage.
[src:pomace/ancient-greek-wine] Wine was almost always diluted, usually with water (or snow when the wine was to be served cold).
[src:pomace/ancient-greek-wine] The Greeks believed that only barbarians drank unmixed or undiluted wine and that the Spartan king Cleomenes I was once driven insane after drinking wine this way.
[src:pomace/ancient-greek-wine] They also believed that undiluted wine could even kill the drinker: the Gallic chieftain Brennus was recorded as having committed suicide by drinking wine full-strength.
[src:pomace/ancient-greek-wine] Greeks asserted that the dilution of wine with water was a mark of civilized behavior, whose contrast was embodied in the myth of the battle of Lapiths with the Centaurs, inflamed to rape and mayhem because of wine drunk undiluted with water.
[src:pomace/ancient-greek-wine] In addition to its significance as a trade commodity, wine also served important religious, social and medical purposes in Greek society.
[src:pomace/ancient-greek-wine] The "feast of the wine" (*me-tu-wo ne-wo*) was a festival in Mycenaean Greece celebrating the "month of the new wine." The cult of Dionysus was very active, if not mysterious, and was immortalized in Euripides's play *The Bacchae*.
[src:pomace/ancient-greek-wine] Several festivals were held throughout the year in honor of the God of wine.
[src:pomace/ancient-greek-wine] February's Anthesteria marked the opening of the wine jars from the previous autumn harvest, featuring wine-drinking contests and a procession through Athens carrying wine jars.
[src:pomace/ancient-greek-wine] The Dionysia included theatrical performances of both comedies and tragedies in honor of the God of wine.
[src:pomace/ancient-greek-wine] Wine was a frequent component at the symposium, which sometimes included the game of *kottabos*, which involved flinging lees from a wine cup towards a target.
[src:pomace/ancient-greek-wine] The medicinal use of wine was frequently studied by the Greeks, including Hippocrates, who did extensive research on the topic.
[src:pomace/ancient-greek-wine] He used wine as a cure for fevers, to ease convalescence and as an antiseptic.
[src:pomace/ancient-greek-wine] He also studied the effect of wine on his patients' stool.
[src:pomace/ancient-greek-wine] Various types of wine were prescribed by Greek doctors for use as an analgesic, diuretic, tonic and digestive aid.
[src:pomace/ancient-greek-wine] The Greeks were also aware of some negative health effects, especially those arising from the consumption of wine beyond moderation.
[src:pomace/ancient-greek-wine] Athenaeus made frequent mention of wine's ability to induce hangover and suggested various remedies for it.
[src:pomace/ancient-greek-wine] The poet Eubulus noted that three bowls (*kylikes*) were the ideal amount of wine to consume.
[src:pomace/ancient-greek-wine] The quantity of three bowls to represent moderation is a recurring theme throughout Greek writing (today, the standard 750 ml bottle contains roughly three to six glasses of wine, depending on serving size).
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Three centuries after the decline of Mycenaean Greece during the Bronze Age collapse, Greek urban poleis began to form in the 8th century BC, ushering in the Archaic period and the colonization of the Mediterranean Basin.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] This was followed by the age of Classical Greece, from the Greco-Persian Wars to the death of Alexander the Great in 323 BC, and which included the Golden Age of Athens and the Peloponnesian War between Athens and Sparta.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] The unification of Greece by Macedon under Philip II and subsequent conquest of the Achaemenid Empire by Alexander the Great spread Hellenistic civilization across the Middle East.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] The Hellenistic period is considered to have ended in 30 BC, when the last Hellenistic kingdom, Ptolemaic Egypt, was annexed by the Roman Republic.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Classical Greek culture, especially philosophy, had a powerful influence on ancient Rome, which carried a version of it throughout the Mediterranean and much of Europe.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] For this reason, Classical Greece is generally considered the cradle of Western civilization, the seminal culture from which the modern West derives many of its founding archetypes and ideas in politics, philosophy, science, and art.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Classical antiquity in the Mediterranean region is commonly considered to have begun in the 8th century BC (around the time of the earliest recorded poetry of Homer) and ended in the 6th century AD.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Classical antiquity in Greece was preceded by the Greek Dark Ages (c.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] 800 BC), archaeologically characterised by the protogeometric and geometric styles of designs on pottery.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Following the Dark Ages was the Archaic period, beginning around the 8th century BC, which saw early developments in Greek culture and society leading to the Classical period from the Persian invasion of Greece in 480 BC until the death of Alexander the Great in 323 BC.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] The Classical period is characterized by a "classical" style, i.e. one which was considered exemplary by later observers, most famously in the Parthenon of Athens.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Politically, the Classical period was dominated by Athens and the Delian League during the 5th century, but displaced by Spartan hegemony during the early 4th century BC, before power shifted to Thebes and the Boeotian League and finally to the League of Corinth led by Macedon.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] This period was shaped by the Greco-Persian Wars, the Peloponnesian War, and the Rise of Macedon.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Following the Classical period was the Hellenistic period (323–146 BC), during which Greek culture and power expanded into the Near East from the death of Alexander until the Roman conquest.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Roman Greece is usually counted from the Roman victory over the Corinthians at the Battle of Corinth in 146 BC to the establishment of Byzantium by Constantine as the capital of the Roman Empire in 330 AD.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Finally, Late Antiquity refers to the period of Christianization during the later 4th to early 6th centuries AD, consummated by the closure of the Academy of Athens by Justinian I in 529.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] The historical period of ancient Greece is unique in world history as the first period attested directly in comprehensive, narrative historiography, while earlier ancient history or protohistory is known from much more fragmentary documents such as annals, king lists, and pragmatic epigraphy.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Herodotus is widely known as the "father of history": his *Histories* are eponymous of the entire field.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Written between the 450s and 420s BC, Herodotus' work reaches about a century into the past, discussing 6th-century BC historical figures such as Darius I of Persia, Cambyses II and Psamtik III, and alluding to some 8th-century BC persons such as Candaules.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] The accuracy of Herodotus' works is debated.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Herodotus was succeeded by authors such as Thucydides, Xenophon, Demosthenes, Plato and Aristotle.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Most were either Athenian or pro-Athenian, which is why far more is known about the history and politics of Athens than of many other cities.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Their scope is further limited by a focus on political, military and diplomatic history, ignoring economic and social history.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] The archaic period, lasting approximately from 800 to 500 BC, saw the culmination of political and social developments which had begun in the Greek Dark Age, with the *polis* (city-state) becoming the most important unit of political organisation in Greece.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] The absence of powerful states in Greece after the collapse of Mycenaean power, and the geography of Greece, where many settlements were separated from their neighbours by mountainous terrain, encouraged the development of small independent city-states.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Several Greek states saw tyrants rise to power in this period, most famously at Corinth from 657 BC.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] The period also saw the founding of Greek colonies around the Mediterranean, with Euboean settlements at Al-Mina in the east as early as 800 BC, and Ischia in the west by 775.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Increasing contact with non-Greek peoples in this period, especially in the Near East, inspired developments in art and architecture, the adoption of coinage, and the development of the Greek alphabet.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Athens developed its democratic system over the course of the archaic period.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Already in the 7th century, the right of all citizen men to attend the assembly appears to have been established.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] After a failed coup led by Cylon of Athens around 636 BC, Draco was appointed to establish a code of laws in 621.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] This failed to reduce the political tension between the poor and the elites, and in 594 Solon was given the authority to enact another set of reforms, which attempted to balance the power of the rich and the poor.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] In the middle of the 6th century, Pisistratus established himself as a tyrant, and after his death in 527 his son Hippias inherited his position; by the end of the 6th century he had been overthrown, and Cleisthenes carried out further democratising reforms.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] In Sparta, a political system with two kings, a council of elders, and five ephors developed over the course of the 8th and 7th centuries.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] According to Spartan tradition, this constitution was established by the legendary lawgiver Lycurgus.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Over the course of the First Messenian War and Second Messenian War, Sparta subjugated the neighbouring region of Messenia, enserfing the population.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] In the 6th century, Greek city-states began to develop formal relationships with one another, where previously individual rulers had relied on personal relationships with the elites of other cities.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Towards the end of the Archaic period, Sparta began to build a series of alliances, the Peloponnesian League, with cities including Corinth, Elis, and Megara, isolating Messenia and reinforcing Sparta's position against Argos, the other major power in the Peloponnese.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Other alliances in the 6th century included those between Elis and Heraea in the Peloponnese; and between the Greek colony Sybaris in southern Italy, its allies, and the Serdaioi.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] In 499 BC, the Ionian city-states under Persian rule rebelled against their Persian-supported tyrant rulers.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Supported by troops sent from Athens and Eretria, they advanced as far as Sardis and burnt the city before being driven back by a Persian counterattack.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] The revolt continued until 494, when the rebelling Ionians were defeated.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Darius did not forget that Athens had assisted the Ionian revolt, and in 490 he assembled an armada to retaliate.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Though heavily outnumbered, the Athenians—supported by their Plataean allies—defeated the Persian hordes at the Battle of Marathon, and the Persian fleet turned tail.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Ten years later, a second invasion was launched by Darius' son Xerxes.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] The city-states of northern and central Greece submitted to the Persian forces without resistance, but a coalition of 31 Greek city-states, including Athens and Sparta, determined to resist the Persian invaders.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] At the same time, Greek Sicily was invaded by a Carthaginian force.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] The Persians were decisively defeated at sea by a primarily Athenian naval force at the Battle of Salamis, and on land in 479 BC at the Battle of Plataea.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] The alliance against Persia continued, initially led by the Spartan Pausanias but from 477 by Athens, and by 460 Persia had been driven out of the Aegean.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] During this long campaign, the Delian League gradually transformed from a defensive alliance of Greek states into an Athenian empire, as Athens' growing naval power intimidated the other league states.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Athens ended its campaigns against Persia in 450, after a disastrous defeat in Egypt in 454, and the death of Cimon in action against the Persians on Cyprus in 450.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] As the Athenian fight against the Persian empire waned, conflict grew between Athens and Sparta.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Suspicious of the increasing Athenian power funded by the Delian League, Sparta offered aid to reluctant members of the League to rebel against Athenian domination.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] These tensions were exacerbated in 462 BC when Athens sent a force to aid Sparta in overcoming a helot revolt, but this aid was rejected by the Spartans.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] In the 450s, Athens took control of Boeotia, and won victories over Aegina and Corinth.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] However, Athens failed to win a decisive victory, and in 447 lost Boeotia again.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Athens and Sparta signed the Thirty Years' Peace in the winter of 446/445, ending the conflict.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Despite the treaty, Athenian relations with Sparta declined again in the 430s, and in 431 BC the Peloponnesian War began.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] The first phase of the war saw a series of fruitless annual invasions of Attica by Sparta, while Athens successfully fought the Corinthian empire in northwest Greece and defended its own empire, despite a plague which killed the leading Athenian statesman Pericles.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] The war turned after Athenian victories led by Cleon at Pylos and Sphakteria, and Sparta sued for peace, but the Athenians rejected the proposal.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] The Athenian failure to regain control of Boeotia at Delium and Brasidas' successes in northern Greece in 424 improved Sparta's position after Sphakteria.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] After the deaths of Cleon and Brasidas, the strongest proponents of war on each side, a peace treaty was negotiated in 421 by the Athenian general Nicias.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] In 418 BC allied forces of Athens and Argos were defeated by Sparta at Mantinea.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] In 415 Athens launched an ambitious naval expedition to dominate Sicily; the expedition ended in disaster at the harbor of Syracuse, with almost the entire army killed, and the ships destroyed.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Soon after the Athenian defeat in Syracuse, Athens' Ionian allies began to rebel against the Delian league, while Persia began to once again involve itself in Greek affairs on the Spartan side.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Initially the Athenian position continued relatively strong, with important victories at Cyzicus in 410 and Arginusae in 406.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] However, in 405 the Spartan Lysander defeated Athens in the Battle of Aegospotami, and began to blockade Athens' harbour; driven by hunger, Athens sued for peace, agreeing to surrender their fleet and join the Spartan-led Peloponnesian League.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Following the Athenian surrender, Sparta installed an oligarchic regime, the Thirty Tyrants, in Athens, one of a number of Spartan-backed oligarchies which rose to power after the Peloponnesian war.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Spartan predominance did not last: after only a year, the Thirty had been overthrown.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] The first half of the 4th century saw the major Greek states attempt to dominate the mainland; none were successful, and their resulting weakness led to a power vacuum which was eventually filled by Macedon under Philip II and then Alexander the Great.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] In the immediate aftermath of the Peloponnesian war, Sparta attempted to extend their own power, leading Argos, Athens, Corinth, and Thebes to join against them.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Aiming to prevent any single Greek state gaining the dominance that would allow it to challenge Persia, the Persian king initially joined the alliance against Sparta, before imposing the Peace of Antalcidas ("King's Peace") which restored Persia's control over the Anatolian Greeks.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] By 371 BC, Thebes was in the ascendancy, defeating Sparta at the Battle of Leuctra, killing the Spartan king Cleombrotus I, and invading Laconia.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Further Theban successes against Sparta in 369 led to Messenia gaining independence; Sparta never recovered from the loss of Messenia's fertile land and the helot workforce it provided.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] The rising power of Thebes led Sparta and Athens to join forces; in 362 they were defeated by Thebes at the Battle of Mantinea.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] In the aftermath of Mantinea, none of the major Greek states were able to dominate.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Though Thebes had won the battle, their general Epaminondas was killed, and they spent the following decades embroiled in wars with their neighbours; Athens, meanwhile, saw its second naval alliance, formed in 377, collapse in the mid-350s.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] The power vacuum in Greece after the Battle of Mantinea was filled by Macedon, under Philip II, starting from the battle of Crocus field.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] In 338 BC, he defeated a Greek alliance at the Battle of Chaeronea, and subsequently formed the League of Corinth.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Philip planned to lead the League to invade Persia, but was murdered in 336 BC.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] His son Alexander the Great was left to fulfill his father's ambitions.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] After campaigns against Macedon's western and northern enemies, and those Greek states that had broken from the League of Corinth following the death of Philip, Alexander began his campaign against Persia in 334 BC.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] He conquered Persia, defeating Darius III at the Battle of Issus in 333 BC, and after the Battle of Gaugamela in 331 BC proclaimed himself king of Asia.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] From 329 BC he led expeditions to Bactria and then India; further plans to invade Arabia and North Africa were halted by his death in 323 BC.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] The period from the death of Alexander the Great in 323 BC until the death of Cleopatra, the last Macedonian ruler of Egypt, is known as the Hellenistic period.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] In the early part of this period, a new form of kingship developed based on Macedonian and Near Eastern traditions.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] The first Hellenistic kings were previously Alexander's generals, and took power in the period following his death, though they were not part of existing royal lineages and lacked historic claims to the territories they controlled.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] In the early part of the Hellenistic period, the exact borders of the Hellenistic kingdoms were not settled.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Antigonus attempted to expand his territory by attacking the other successor kingdoms until they joined against him, and he was killed at the Battle of Ipsus in 301 BC.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] His son Demetrius spent many years in Seleucid captivity, and his son, Antigonus II, only reclaimed the Macedonian throne around 276.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Meanwhile, the Seleucid kingdom gave up territory in the east to the Indian king Chandragupta Maurya in exchange for war elephants, and later lost large parts of Persia to the Parthian Empire.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] By the mid-3rd century, the kingdoms of Alexander's successors was mostly stable, though there continued to be disputes over border areas.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] The great capitals of Hellenistic culture were Alexandria in the Ptolemaic Kingdom and Antioch in the Seleucid Empire.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] The conquests of Alexander had numerous consequences for the Greek city-states.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] It greatly widened the horizons of the Greeks and led to a steady emigration of the young and ambitious to the new Greek empires in the east.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Many Greeks migrated to Alexandria, Antioch and the many other new Hellenistic cities founded in Alexander's wake, as far away as present-day Afghanistan and Pakistan, where the Greco-Bactrian Kingdom and the Indo-Greek Kingdom survived until the end of the 1st century BC.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Some city-states within Greece formed themselves into two major leagues; the Achaean League (including Corinth and Argos) and the Aetolian League.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] For much of the period until the Roman conquest, these leagues were at war, often participating in the conflicts between the Diadochi's successor states to Alexander's empire.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] The Antigonid Kingdom became involved in a war with the Roman Republic in the late 3rd century.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Although the First Macedonian War was inconclusive, the Romans, in typical fashion, continued to fight Macedon until it was completely absorbed into the Roman Republic (by 149 BC).
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] In the east, the unwieldy Seleucid Empire gradually disintegrated, although a rump survived until 64 BC, whilst the Ptolemaic Kingdom continued in Egypt until 30 BC when it too was conquered by the Romans.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] The Aetolian league grew wary of Roman involvement in Greece, and sided with the Seleucids in the Roman–Seleucid War; when the Romans were victorious, the league was effectively absorbed into the Republic.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Although the Achaean league outlasted both the Aetolian league and Macedon, it was also soon defeated and absorbed by the Romans in 146 BC, bringing Greek independence to an end.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] The Greek peninsula came under Roman rule during the 146 BC conquest of Greece after the Battle of Corinth.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Macedonia became a Roman province while southern Greece came under the surveillance of Macedonia's prefect; however, some Greek *poleis* managed to maintain a partial independence and avoid taxation.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] The Aegean Islands were added to this territory in 133 BC.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Athens and other Greek cities revolted in 88 BC, and the peninsula was crushed by the Roman general Sulla.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] The Roman civil wars devastated the land even further, until Augustus organized the peninsula as the province of Achaea in 27 BC.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Greece was a key eastern province of the Roman Empire, as the Roman culture had long been in fact Greco-Roman.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] The Greek language served as a *lingua franca* in the East and in Italy, and many Greek intellectuals such as Galen would perform most of their work in Rome.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] The territory of Greece is mountainous, and as a result, ancient Greece consisted of many smaller regions, each with its own dialect, cultural peculiarities, and identity.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Regionalism and regional conflicts were prominent features of ancient Greece.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Cities tended to be located in valleys between mountains, or on coastal plains, and dominated a certain area around them.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] In the south lay the Peloponnese, consisting of the regions of Laconia (southeast), Messenia (southwest), Elis (west), Achaia (north), Korinthia (northeast), Argolis (east), and Arcadia (center).
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] These names survive to the present day as regional units of modern Greece, though with somewhat different boundaries.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Mainland Greece to the north, nowadays known as Central Greece, consisted of Aetolia and Acarnania in the west, Locris, Doris, and Phocis in the center, while in the east lay Boeotia, Attica, and Megaris.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Northeast lay Thessaly, while Epirus lay to the northwest.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Epirus stretched from the Ambracian Gulf in the south to the Ceraunian Mountains and the Aoos river in the north, and consisted of Chaonia (north), Molossia (center), and Thesprotia (south).
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] In the northeast corner was Macedonia, originally consisting Lower Macedonia and its regions, such as Emathia (Macedonia), Pieria, and Bottiaea, and later Almopia, Amphaxitis.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] The original capital of Macedon was Aigai and then moved to Pella in the 4th century BC.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] To the north of Macedonia lay various non-Greek peoples such as the Paeonians due north, the Thracians to the northeast, and the Illyrians, with whom the Macedonians were frequently in conflict, to the northwest.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Chalcidice was settled early on by southern Greek colonists and was considered part of the Greek world, while from the late 2nd millennium BC substantial Greek settlement also occurred on the eastern shores of the Aegean, in Anatolia.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] This was not simply for trade, but also to found settlements.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] These Greek colonies were not, as Roman colonies were, dependent on their mother-city, but were independent city-states in their own right.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Greeks settled outside of Greece in two distinct ways.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] The first was in permanent settlements founded by Greeks, which formed as independent poleis.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] The second form was in what historians refer to as *emporia*; trading posts which were occupied by both Greeks and non-Greeks and which were primarily concerned with the manufacture and sale of goods.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Examples of this latter type of settlement are found at Al Mina in the east and Pithekoussai in the west.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] From around 750 to 500 BC, Greeks settled colonies in all directions.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] To the east, the Aegean coast of Asia Minor was colonized first, followed by Cyprus and the coasts of Thrace, the Sea of Marmara and the south coast of the Black Sea.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Eventually, Greek colonization reached as far northeast as present-day Ukraine and Russia (Taganrog).
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] To the west the coasts of Illyria, Southern Italy (called "Magna Graecia") were settled, followed by Southern France, Corsica, and even eastern Spain.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Greek colonies were also founded in Egypt and Libya.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Modern Syracuse, Naples, Marseille and Istanbul had their beginnings as the Greek colonies Syracusae (Συράκουσαι), Neapolis (Νεάπολις), Massalia (Μασσαλία) and Byzantion (Βυζάντιον).
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] These colonies played an important role in the spread of Greek influence throughout Europe and also aided in the establishment of long-distance trading networks between the Greek city-states, boosting the economy of ancient Greece.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Ancient Greece consisted of several hundred relatively independent city-states (*poleis*).
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] This was a situation unlike that in most other contemporary societies, which were either tribal or kingdoms ruling over relatively large territories.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Undoubtedly, the geography of Greece—divided and sub-divided by hills, mountains, and rivers—contributed to the fragmentary nature of ancient Greece.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] On the one hand, the ancient Greeks had no doubt that they were "one people"; they had the same religion, same basic culture, and same language.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Furthermore, the Greeks were very aware of their tribal origins; Herodotus was able to extensively categorise the city-states by tribe.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Yet, although these higher-level relationships existed, they seem to have rarely had a major role in Greek politics.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] The independence of the *poleis* was fiercely defended; unification was something rarely contemplated by the ancient Greeks.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Even when, during the second Persian invasion of Greece, a group of city-states allied themselves to defend Greece, the vast majority of *poleis* remained neutral, and after the Persian defeat, the allies quickly returned to infighting.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Thus, the major peculiarities of the ancient Greek political system were its fragmented nature (and that this does not particularly seem to have tribal origin), and the particular focus on urban centers within otherwise tiny states.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] The peculiarities of the Greek system are further evidenced by the colonies that they set up throughout the Mediterranean, which, though they might count a certain Greek *polis* as their 'mother' (and remain sympathetic to her), were completely independent of the founding city.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Inevitably smaller *poleis* might be dominated by larger neighbors, but conquest or direct rule by another city-state appears to have been quite rare.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Instead the *poleis* grouped themselves into leagues, membership of which was in a constant state of flux.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Later in the Classical period, the leagues would become fewer and larger, be dominated by one city (particularly Athens, Sparta and Thebes); and often *poleis* would be compelled to join under threat of war (or as part of a peace treaty).
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Even after Philip II of Macedon conquered the heartlands of ancient Greece, he did not attempt to annex the territory or unify it into a new province, but compelled most of the *poleis* to join his own Corinthian League.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Initially many Greek city-states seem to have been petty kingdoms; there was often a city official carrying some residual, ceremonial functions of the king (*basileus*), e.g., the *archon basileus* in Athens.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] However, by the Archaic period and the first historical consciousness, most had already become aristocratic oligarchies.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] It is unclear exactly how this change occurred.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] For instance, in Athens, the kingship had been reduced to a hereditary, lifelong chief magistracy (*archon*) by c.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] 1050 BC; by 753 BC this had become a decennial, elected archonship, and finally an annually elected archonship by 683 BC.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Through each stage, more power would have been transferred to the aristocracy as a whole, and away from a single individual.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Inevitably, the domination of politics and concomitant aggregation of wealth by small groups of families was apt to cause social unrest in many *poleis*.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] In many cities a tyrant (not in the modern sense of repressive autocracies), would at some point seize control and govern according to their own will; often a populist agenda would help sustain them in power.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] In a system wracked with class conflict, government by a 'strongman' was often the best solution.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Athens fell under a tyranny in the second half of the 6th century BC.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] When this tyranny was ended, the Athenians founded the world's first democracy as a radical solution to prevent the aristocracy regaining power.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] A citizens' assembly (the *Ecclesia*), for the discussion of city policy, had existed since the reforms of Draco in 621 BC; all citizens were permitted to attend after the reforms of Solon (early 6th century), but the poorest citizens could not address the assembly or run for office.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] With the establishment of the democracy, the assembly became the *de jure* mechanism of government; all citizens had equal privileges in the assembly.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] However, non-citizens, such as metics (foreigners living in Athens) or slaves, had no political rights at all.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] After the rise of democracy in Athens, other city-states founded democracies.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] However, many retained more traditional forms of government.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] As so often in other matters, Sparta was a notable exception to the rest of Greece, ruled through the whole period by not one, but two hereditary monarchs.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] The Kings of Sparta belonged to the Agiads and the Eurypontids, descendants respectively of Eurysthenes and Procles.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Both dynasties' founders were believed to be twin sons of Aristodemus, a Heraclid ruler.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] However, the powers of these kings were held in check by both a council of elders (the *Gerousia*) and magistrates specifically appointed to watch over the kings (the *Ephors*).
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Only free, land-owning, native-born men could be citizens entitled to the full protection of the law in a city-state.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] In most city-states, unlike the situation in Rome, social prominence did not allow special rights.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Sometimes families controlled public religious functions, but this ordinarily did not give any extra power in the government.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] In Athens, the population was divided into four social classes based on wealth.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] People could change classes if they made more money.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] In Sparta, all male citizens were called *homoioi*, meaning "peers".
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] However, Spartan kings, who served as the city-state's dual military and religious leaders, came from two families.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Women in Ancient Greece appear to have primarily performed domestic tasks, managed households, and borne and reared children.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Slaves had the right to have a family and own property, subject to their master's goodwill and permission, but they had no political rights.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] By 600 BC, chattel slavery had spread in Greece.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] By the 5th century BC, slaves made up one-third of the total population in some city-states.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Between 40 and 80% of the population of Classical Athens were slaves.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Slaves outside of Sparta almost never revolted because they were made up of too many nationalities and were too scattered to organize.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] However, unlike later Western culture, the ancient Greeks did not think in terms of race.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Most families owned slaves as household servants and laborers, and even poor families might have owned a few slaves.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Owners were not allowed to beat or kill their slaves.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Owners often promised to free slaves in the future to encourage slaves to work hard.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Unlike in Rome, freedmen did not become citizens.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Instead, they were mixed into the population of *metics*, which included people from foreign countries or other city-states who were officially allowed to live in the state.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] These public slaves had a larger measure of independence than slaves owned by families, living on their own and performing specialized tasks.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] In Athens, public slaves were trained to look out for counterfeit coinage, while temple slaves acted as servants of the temple's deity and Scythian slaves were employed in Athens as a police force corralling citizens to political functions.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Sparta had a special type of slaves called *helots*.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Helots were Messenians enslaved en masse during the Messenian Wars by the state and assigned to families where they were forced to stay.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Helots raised food and did household chores so that women could concentrate on raising strong children while men could devote their time to training as hoplites.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Their masters treated them harshly, and helots revolted against their masters several times.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] In 370/369 BC, as a result of Epaminondas' liberation of Messenia from Spartan rule, the helot system there came to an end and the helots won their freedom.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] However, it persisted in Laconia until the 2nd century BC.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] For most of Greek history, education was private, except in Sparta.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] During the Hellenistic period, some city-states established public schools.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Only wealthy families could afford a teacher.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Boys learned how to read, write and quote literature.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] They also learned to sing and play one musical instrument and were trained as athletes for military service.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] They studied not for a job but to become an effective citizen.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Girls also learned to read, write and do simple arithmetic so they could manage the household.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] They almost never received education after childhood.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Boys went to school at the age of seven, or went to the barracks, if they lived in Sparta.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] The three types of teachings were: grammatistes for arithmetic, kitharistes for music and dancing, and Paedotribae for sports.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Boys from wealthy families attending the private school lessons were taken care of by a *paidagogos*, a household slave selected for this task who accompanied the boy during the day.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Classes were held in teachers' private houses and included reading, writing, mathematics, singing, and playing the lyre and flute.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] When the boy became 12 years old the schooling started to include sports such as wrestling, running, and throwing discus and javelin.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] In Athens, some older youths attended academy for the finer disciplines such as culture, sciences, music, and the arts.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] The schooling ended at age 18, followed by military training in the army usually for one or two years.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Some of Athens' greatest such schools included the Lyceum (the so-called Peripatetic school founded by Aristotle of Stageira) and the Platonic Academy (founded by Plato of Athens).
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] The education system of the wealthy ancient Greeks is also called Paideia.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] At its economic height in the 5th and 4th centuries BC, the free citizenry of Classical Greece represented perhaps the most prosperous society in the ancient world, some economic historians considering Greece one of the most advanced pre-industrial economies.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] In terms of wheat, wages reached an estimated 7–12 kg (15–26 lb) daily for an unskilled worker in urban Athens, 2–3 times the 3.75 kg (8.3 lb) of an unskilled rural labourer in Roman Egypt, though Greek farm incomes too were on average lower than those available to urban workers.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] At least in the Archaic period, the fragmentary nature of ancient Greece, with many competing city-states, increased the frequency of conflict but conversely limited the scale of warfare.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Unable to maintain professional armies, the city-states relied on their own citizens to fight.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] This inevitably reduced the potential duration of campaigns, as citizens would need to return to their own professions (especially in the case of, for example, farmers).
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Campaigns would therefore often be restricted to summer.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] When battles occurred, they were usually set piece and intended to be decisive.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Casualties were slight compared to later battles, rarely amounting to more than five percent of the losing side, but the slain often included the most prominent citizens and generals who led from the front.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] The scale and scope of warfare in ancient Greece changed dramatically as a result of the Greco-Persian Wars.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] To fight the enormous armies of the Achaemenid Empire was effectively beyond the capabilities of a single city-state.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] The eventual triumph of the Greeks was achieved by alliances of city-states (the exact composition changing over time), allowing the pooling of resources and division of labor.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Although alliances between city-states occurred before this time, nothing on this scale had been seen before.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] The rise of Athens and Sparta as pre-eminent powers during this conflict led directly to the Peloponnesian War, which saw further development of the nature of warfare, strategy and tactics.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Fought between leagues of cities dominated by Athens and Sparta, the increased manpower and financial resources increased the scale and allowed the diversification of warfare.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Set-piece battles during the Peloponnesian war proved indecisive and instead there was increased reliance on attritionary strategies, naval battles and blockades and sieges.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] These changes greatly increased the number of casualties and the disruption of Greek society.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Athens owned one of the largest war fleets in ancient Greece.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] It had over 200 triremes each powered by 170 oarsmen who were seated in 3 rows on each side of the ship.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] The city could afford such a large fleet—it had over 34,000 oarsmen—because it owned a lot of silver mines that were worked by slaves.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] According to Josiah Ober, Greek city-states faced approximately a one-in-three chance of destruction during the archaic and classical period.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Ancient Greek philosophy focused on the role of reason and inquiry.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] In many ways, it had an important influence on modern philosophy, as well as modern science.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Clear unbroken lines of influence lead from ancient Greek and Hellenistic philosophers, to medieval Muslim philosophers and Islamic scientists, to the European Renaissance and Enlightenment, to the secular sciences of the modern day.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Neither reason nor inquiry began with the ancient Greeks.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Defining the difference between the Greek quest for knowledge and the quests of the elder civilizations, such as the ancient Egyptians and Babylonians, has long been a topic of study by theorists of civilization.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] The first known philosophers of Greece were the pre-Socratics, who attempted to provide naturalistic, non-mythical descriptions of the world.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] They were followed by Socrates, one of the first philosophers based in Athens during its golden age whose ideas, despite being known by second-hand accounts instead of writings of his own, laid the basis of Western philosophy.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Socrates' disciple Plato, who wrote *The Republic* and established a radical difference between ideas and the concrete world, and Plato's disciple Aristotle, who wrote extensively about nature and ethics, are also immensely influential in Western philosophy to this day.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] The later Hellenistic philosophy, also originating in Greece, is defined by names such as Antisthenes (cynicism), Zeno of Citium (stoicism) and Plotinus (Neoplatonism).
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] The earliest Greek literature was poetry and was composed for performance rather than private consumption.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] The earliest Greek poet known is Homer, although he was certainly part of an existing tradition of oral poetry.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Homer's poetry, though it was developed around the same time that the Greeks developed writing, would have been composed orally; the first poet to certainly compose their work in writing was Archilochus, a lyric poet from the mid-7th century BC.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Tragedy developed around the end of the archaic period, taking elements from across the pre-existing genres of late archaic poetry.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Like poetry, Greek prose had its origins in the archaic period, and the earliest writers of Greek philosophy, history, and medical literature all date to the 6th century BC.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Prose first emerged as the writing style adopted by the presocratic philosophers Anaximander and Anaximenes—though Thales of Miletus, considered the first Greek philosopher, apparently wrote nothing.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Prose as a genre reached maturity in the classical era, and the major Greek prose genres—philosophy, history, rhetoric, and dialogue—developed in this period.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] The Hellenistic period saw the literary centre of the Greek world move from Athens, where it had been in the classical period, to Alexandria.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] At the same time, other Hellenistic kings such as the Antigonids and the Attalids were patrons of scholarship and literature, turning Pella and Pergamon respectively into cultural centres.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] It was thanks to this cultural patronage by Hellenistic kings, and especially the Museum at Alexandria, that so much ancient Greek literature has survived.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] The Library of Alexandria, part of the Museum, had the previously unenvisaged aim of collecting together copies of all known authors in Greek.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Almost all of the surviving non-technical Hellenistic literature is poetry, and Hellenistic poetry tended to be highly intellectual, blending different genres and traditions, and avoiding linear narratives.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] The Hellenistic period also saw a shift in the ways literature was consumed—while in the archaic and classical periods literature had typically been experienced in public performance, in the Hellenistic period it was more commonly read privately.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] At the same time, Hellenistic poets began to write for private, rather than public, consumption.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] With Octavian's victory at Actium in 31 BC, Rome began to become a major centre of Greek literature, as important Greek authors such as Strabo and Dionysius of Halicarnassus came to Rome.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] The period of greatest innovation in Greek literature under Rome was the "long second century" from approximately 80 AD to around 230 AD.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] This innovation was especially marked in prose, with the development of the novel and a revival of prominence for display oratory both dating to this period.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] In Ancient Greek society, music was ever-present and considered a fundamental component of civilisation.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] It was an important part of public religious worship, private ceremonies such as weddings and funerals, and household entertainment.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Men sang and played music at the symposium; both men and women sang at work; and children's games involved song and dance.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Ancient Greek music was primarily vocal, sung either by a solo singer or a chorus, and usually accompanied by an instrument; purely instrumental music was less common.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] The Greeks used stringed instruments, including lyres, harps, and lutes; and wind instruments, of which the most important was the *aulos*, a reed instrument.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Percussion instruments played a relatively unimportant role supporting stringed and wind instruments, and were used in certain religious cults.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Ancient Greek mathematics contributed many important developments to mathematics, including the basic rules of geometry, the idea of formal mathematical proof, and discoveries in number theory, mathematical analysis, applied mathematics, and approached close to establishing integral calculus.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] The discoveries of several Greek mathematicians, including Pythagoras, Euclid, and Archimedes, are still used in mathematical teaching today.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] The Greeks developed astronomy, which they treated as a branch of mathematics, to a highly sophisticated level.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] The first geometrical, three-dimensional models to explain the apparent motion of the planets were developed in the 4th century BC by Eudoxus of Cnidus and Callippus of Cyzicus.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Their younger contemporary Heraclides Ponticus proposed that the Earth rotates around its axis.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] In the 3rd century BC, Aristarchus of Samos was the first to suggest a heliocentric system.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Archimedes in his treatise The Sand Reckoner revives Aristarchus' hypothesis that *"the fixed stars and the Sun remain unmoved, while the Earth revolves about the Sun on the circumference of a circle"*.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Otherwise, only fragmentary descriptions of Aristarchus' idea survive.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Eratosthenes, using the angles of shadows created at widely separated regions, estimated the circumference of the Earth with great accuracy.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] In the 2nd century BC Hipparchus of Nicea made a number of contributions, including the first measurement of precession and the compilation of the first star catalog in which he proposed the modern system of apparent magnitudes.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] The Antikythera mechanism, a device for calculating the movements of planets, dates from about 80 BC and was the first ancestor of the astronomical computer.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] It was discovered in an ancient shipwreck off the Greek island of Antikythera, between Kythera and Crete.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] The device became famous for its use of a differential gear, previously believed to have been invented in the 16th century, and the miniaturization and complexity of its parts, comparable to a clock made in the 18th century.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] The original mechanism is displayed in the Bronze collection of the National Archaeological Museum of Athens, accompanied by a replica.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] The ancient Greeks also made important discoveries in the medical field.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Hippocrates was a physician of the Classical period, and is considered one of the most outstanding figures in the history of medicine.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] He is referred to as the "father of medicine" in recognition of his lasting contributions to the field as the founder of the Hippocratic school of medicine.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] This intellectual school revolutionized medicine in ancient Greece, establishing it as a discipline distinct from other fields that it had traditionally been associated with (notably theurgy and philosophy), thus making medicine a profession.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] The art of ancient Greece has exercised an enormous influence on the culture of many countries from ancient times to the present day, particularly in the areas of sculpture and architecture.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] In the West, the art of the Roman Empire was largely derived from Greek models.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] In the East, Alexander the Great's conquests initiated several centuries of exchange between Greek, Central Asian and Indian cultures, resulting in Greco-Buddhist art, with ramifications as far as Japan.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Following the Renaissance in Europe, the humanist aesthetic and the high technical standards of Greek art inspired generations of European artists.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Well into the 19th century, the classical tradition derived from Greece dominated the art of the Western world.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Religion was a central part of ancient Greek life.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Though the Greeks of different cities and tribes worshipped similar gods, religious practices were not uniform and the gods were thought of differently in different places.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] The Greeks were polytheistic, worshipping many gods, but as early as the 6th century BC a pantheon of twelve Olympians began to develop.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Greek religion was influenced by the practices of the Greeks' near eastern neighbours at least as early as the archaic period, and by the Hellenistic period this influence was seen in both directions.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] The most important religious act in ancient Greece was animal sacrifice, most commonly of sheep and goats.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Sacrifice was accompanied by public prayer, and prayer and hymns were themselves a major part of ancient Greek religious life.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] The civilization of ancient Greece has been immensely influential on language, politics, educational systems, philosophy, science, and the arts.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] It became the *Leitkultur* of the Roman Empire to the point of marginalizing native Italic traditions.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] Via the Roman Empire, Greek culture came to be foundational to Western culture in general.
[src:pomace/ancient-greeks] A modern revival of Classical Greek learning took place in the Neoclassicism movement in 18th- and 19th-century Europe and the Americas.
[src:pomace/pomace] Grape pomace has traditionally been used to produce pomace brandy (such as grappa, orujo, törkölypálinka, tsipouro, tsikoudia, zivania).
[src:pomace/pomace] Today, it is mostly used as fodder, as fertilizer, or for the extraction of bioactive compounds like polyphenols.
[src:pomace/pomace] The English word *pomace* derives from Medieval Latin *pomaceum* ("cider") and *pomaceus* ("pomaceous, appley"), from Classical Latin *pomum* ("fruit, apple").
[src:pomace/pomace] The word was originally used for cider and only later applied to the apple mash before or after pressing, via various cognate terms in northern French dialects, before being used for such byproducts more generally.
[src:pomace/pomace] The ancient Greeks and Romans used grape pomace to create an inferior class of wine given to slaves and laborers.
[src:pomace/pomace] The grapes were first pressed twice and the resulting pomace was then soaked in water for another day and pressed a third time and fermented.
[src:pomace/pomace] The resulting liquid produced a thin, weak, and thirst-quenching wine with an alcohol content around 3 or 4%, now known as piquette in English and French and as *graspia* or *vin piccolo* in Italian.
[src:pomace/pomace] Piquette was also widely available during the Middle Ages.
[src:pomace/pomace] As medieval wines were not usually fermented to dryness, medieval piquette retained a degree of residual sugar.
[src:pomace/pomace] Pomace from various sources—particularly fish and castor beans—was also used in the early modern period for fertilizer.
[src:pomace/pomace] Olive pomace, the byproduct of olive oil extraction, was widely used throughout classical antiquity as an alternative fuel source to wood and charcoal.
[src:pomace/pomace] Use of olive pomace peaked in the Roman era, when, due to urban growth and proto-industrial activity, markets for imported olive pomace developed.
[src:pomace/pomace] Olive pomace may be sun-dried or made into charcoal for use as fuel.
[src:pomace/pomace] Apple pomace is often used to produce pectin and can be used to make ciderkin, a weak cider, as well as white cider, a strong and colourless alcoholic drink.
[src:pomace/pomace] Grape pomace is used to produce pomace brandy and piquette.
[src:pomace/pomace] Most wine-producing cultures began making some type of pomace brandy after the principles of distillation were understood.
[src:pomace/pomace] Pomace in winemaking differs, depending upon whether white wine or red wine is being produced.
[src:pomace/pomace] In red wine production, pomace is produced after the free run juice (the juice created before pressing by the weight of gravity) is poured off, leaving behind dark blackish-red pomace consisting of grape skins and stems.
[src:pomace/pomace] The color of red wine is derived from skin contact during the maceration period, which sometimes includes partial fermentation.
[src:pomace/pomace] The resulting pomace is more alcoholic and tannic than pomace produced from white wine production.
[src:pomace/pomace] Pomace from the Italian wine Amarone is macerated in Valpolicella wine to produce Ripasso.
[src:pomace/pomace] In white wine production, grapes are separated from their skins, then pressed to obtain juice.
[src:pomace/pomace] The skin pomace is a pale, greenish-brown color, and contains residual sugars and tannins.
[src:pomace/pomace] This pomace is used in brandy production.
[src:pomace/pomace] Top, white grape pomace; bottom, red grape pomace.
[src:pomace/pomace] Pomace is produced in large quantities in wine production, making its disposal an important environmental consideration.
[src:pomace/pomace] Some wineries use the material as fertilizer, while others are selling it to biogas companies for renewable energy.
[src:pomace/pomace] As envisioned, pomace would be introduced into anaerobic digesters that contain microorganisms that aid in its decomposition and produce methane gas that could be burnt to generate power.
[src:pomace/pomace] Specific polyphenols in red wine pomace may be beneficial for dental hygiene.
[src:pomace/pomace] A study conducted at the Eastman Dental Center found that these polyphenols interfere with *Streptococcus mutans*, the bacterium in the mouth that causes tooth decay.
[src:pomace/pomace] Professor Hyun Koo, the lead researcher of the study, hoped as of 2008 to isolate these polyphenols to produce new mouthwashes that will help protect against cavities.
[src:pomace/pomace] Grape pomace is also used in the oil and gas industry as a lost circulation material in oil-based drilling muds due to the pomace being fibrous and tannin-rich.
[src:pomace/pomace] A 2004 study conducted by Erciyes University in Turkey found that pomace can also act as a natural food preservative that interferes with *E. coli*, *Salmonella* and *Staphylococcus* bacteria.
[src:pomace/pomace] Researchers pulverised the dried pomace from the white Turkish wine grape Emir Karasi and red Kalecik Karasi grapes; this was mixed with ethyl acetate, methanol or water and exposed to 14 different types of food bacteria.
[src:pomace/pomace] All 14 bacteria were inhibited to some degree by the pomace – depending on the grape variety and the concentration of the extract.
[src:pomace/pomace] The red wine Kalecik Karasi grape was the most effective; the researchers believed this was due to the higher concentration of polyphenols in red wine grape skins.
[src:pomace/pomace] Oenocyanin, a natural red dye and food-coloring agent, is produced from grape pomace.
[src:pomace/pomace] Tartrates (potassium bitartrate, 'cream of tartar') and grape polyphenols can also be manufactured from grape pomace.
[src:pomace/pomace] Apple pomace has long been a traditional feed for various kinds of livestock.
[src:pomace/pomace] The use of grape pomace as livestock feed is encouraged in order to reduce the release of grape processing residues in the environment, which can lead to serious pollution.
[src:pomace/pomace] Apple pomace was used, in conjunction with whey, to flavor the first iteration of Fanta soft drink in Germany during World War II.
[src:pomace/pomace] This was done because wartime embargoes limited Coca-Cola of Germany's ability to import and manufacture the American beverage.
[src:pomace/pomace] Apple pomace can also be milled in order to create apple flour, also known as apple pomace flour.
[src:pomace/pomace] Pomace was once used as an ingredient in some paints, but today such use is limited to artisanal paints in such applications as fine arts or architectural restoration, whereas for industrial and commercial paints it is now superfluous petrochemically.
[src:pomace/pomace] Grape and apple pomace have been used to make plant-based leather.
[src:pomace/pomace] According to the Canadian *Food and Drug Regulations*, pomace can be a potable alcoholic distillate or a mixture of potable alcoholic distillates obtained by distilled skin and pulp of sound ripe fruit after removal of the fruit juice, wine or fruit wine.
[src:pomace/pomace] Pomace may contain caramel, fruit, botanical substances, flavoring and flavoring preparations.
[src:pomace/pomace] Pomace may be described on its label as "(name of the fruit) Pomace" or "(name of the fruit) Marc" if all of the skin and pulp of the fruit used to make the pomace originate from the particular fruit.
